{"title_page": "Dayvid Figler", "text_new": "{{short description|American lawyer}}\n'''Dayvid Figler''' (born August 18, 1967, [[Chicago]], [[Illinois]], United States) is an American performer, author and trial [[lawyer]].  He became one of the youngest lawyers in [[Nevada]] history after successfully taking the bar exam at age 23. In 2003, he began and served a short term as a [[Las Vegas, Nevada|Las Vegas]] municipal court judge after being appointed by Mayor [[Oscar B. Goodman]].<ref>\n{{Citation\n  | last =  \n  | first = \n  | title = The Show Goes on at Municipal Court...\n  | newspaper = The Las Vegas Sun\n  | location = Las Vegas, Nevada\n  | date = 9 January 2003\n  | url = http://www.lasvegassun.com/news/2003/jan/09/the-show-goes-on-at-municipal-court/}}</ref>\nApart from his success as one of the better known criminal defense attorneys in Las Vegas, he has become a regarded legal commentator, one of the most quoted authorities on Las Vegas,<ref>{{Citation\n  | last =  Deutsch\n  | first = Linda\n  | title = Simpson's Future Now Hangs...\n  | newspaper = USA Today\n  | location = Washington, D.C.\n  | date = 7 October 2008\n  | url = http://www.lasvegassun.com/search/?q=figler&author=&from=&to=&sortby=dateand}}</ref>\nand a prolific radio commentator and writer on a variety of topics related to Las Vegas.<ref>\n{{Citation\n | people = Ain't Necessarily So\n | title = KNPR radio\n | url = http://www.knpr.org\n | medium = Radio-Program\n | publisher = Ain't Necessarily So\n | location = Las Vegas, Nevada\n | accessdate =2017-06-30 }}\n</ref>\n\n==Background==\nFigler graduated from the [[University of the Pacific (United States)|University of the Pacific]] \u2013 [[McGeorge School of Law]] in 1991. At McGeorge he served as student body president.  He started his career in his hometown of Las Vegas, where his family relocated in 1971.  Raised in Las Vegas, his unique perspective as a so-called \u201cVegas kid\u201d has produced numerous humor oriented anecdotes which have provided the fodder for hundreds of radio essays which have appeared on Las Vegas National Public Radio affiliate, [[KNPR]], as well as [[NPR]]\u2019s [[All Things Considered]] Program.  He is also an alum of one of the longest running sketch college sketch comedy groups in the nation, [[Comedy Corner]] at the University of Arizona. In 2019, he was awarded the prestigious Medal of Justice honor from the Nevada State Bar.<ref>{{Citation | date = 6 May 2019 | url=https://www.nvbar.org/state-bar-of-nevada-announces-recipients-of-the-2019-membership-awards/|title=State Bar of Nevada Announces Recipients of the 2019 Membership Awards}}</ref>\n\nDayvid Figler served as a congressional intern in Washington, D.C. for now Senate Majority Leader [[Harry M. Reid]] in 1987 and later  completed an internship with the United States Attorneys office in Las Vegas. Upon graduation from law school, he worked for a number of unions and fellow high-profile criminal defense attorney, Dominic Gentile.  Eventually, Figler took an associate position with the Clark County Special Public Defender's office where he exclusively represented indigents charged with murder, including those facing the [[death penalty]].  It is in this office where he began a professional relationship with noted Las Vegas attorney, Kristina Wildeveld that continues to this day.\n\nHe has been cited and quoted as a noted legal expert in many places including the New York Times, National Public Radio, Newsweek, USA Today and the Los Angeles Times.<ref>{{Citation\n  | last = Friess\n  | first = Steve\n  | title = After apologies, Simpson is sentenced...\n  | newspaper = The New York Times\n  | location = New York\n  | date = 6 December 2008\n  | url = https://www.nytimes.com/2008/12/06/us/06simpson.html?scp=9&sq=figler&st=cse }}</ref><ref>{{Citation\n  | last = Robbins\n  | first = Ted\n  | title = O.J. Simpson to be sentenced...\n  | newspaper = National Public Radio\n  | date = 5 December 2008\n  | url =https://www.npr.org/templates/story/story.php?storyId=97843646 }}</ref><ref>{{Citation\n |last=Abowitz \n |first=Richard \n |title=One former Vegas judge on \"juice\"... \n |newspaper=The Los Angeles Times \n |location=Los Angeles, California \n |date=2006-06-13 \n |url=http://vegasblog.latimes.com/vegas/2006/06/one_former_vega.html \n |url-status=dead \n |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110713191421/http://vegasblog.latimes.com/vegas/2006/06/one_former_vega.html \n |archivedate=2011-07-13 \n}}</ref>\n\n==High profile cases==\n===Donte Johnson===\nFigler's first case of note was defending against the death penalty prosecution of Donte Johnson, a California gang member who directed the kidnapping and execution style murders of four young men in Las Vegas in 1998.  The four young men were followers of the band, [[Phish]], and the stated motive for their killing was an attempt to steal money the men had made on the road with Phish.  At trial, evidence was presented that Johnson was responsible for a number of other murders and attempt murders.  The jury, however, did not impose the death penalty after Figler's impassioned closing argument. Later, a 3-judge panel of judges imposed the death penalty.  Arguing one of the first cases in the country in light of the U.S. Supreme Court's 2000 ruling in [[Apprendi v. New Jersey]], Figler successfully advocated the landmark case and in a published opinion, the 3-judge death panels of Nevada were ruled unconstitutional and the Court vacated the imposition of the death penalty.  JOHNSON V. STATE, 118 Nev. Adv. Op. No. 79 (12/18/02)<ref>\n{{Cite court\n  |litigants=Johnson v. State\n  |vol=118\n  |reporter=Nev. Adv. Op.\n  |opinion=79\n  |pinpoint=\n  |court= Nevada Supreme Court\n  |date=2002\n  |url=http://www.nvbar.org/nevada_lawyer_articles3.asp?ID=195 }}</ref>\n\n===Gloria Guzman===\n\nAs a lawyer, Figler was first showcased before a national audience on CourtTV (later TruTV) after the gavel-to-gavel coverage of the trial of Gloria Guzman in 2006.  There, Guzman was a nurse caretaker who fell in love with and married one of her charges in a facility who was also a quadriplegic.  The two moved out of the facility and into an apartment where they engaged in a destructive lifestyle involving methamphetamine and guns. When her husband drowned in a bathtub, Guzman was accused of first degree murder.  Midtrial, Figler discovered that the police had falsified the transcript of her confession and a hasty plea bargain later the previously incarcerated Guzman was given credit for time served.  This case marked the first of numerous appearances for Figler on the [[Nancy Grace]] program both as a guest and a commentator.<ref>Nancy Grace, CNN Headline News, [http://transcripts.cnn.com/TRANSCRIPTS/0608/14/ng.01.html  Plea Deal in Nevada]</ref>  The Nancy Grace appearances led to a number of guest appearances on other TruTV programs including [[Star Jones]],<ref>\n{{Citation\n  | last = Jones\n  | first = Star\n  | title = The Star Jones Program\n  | newspaper = Star Jones\n  | location = New York\n  | date = 18 September 2007\n  | url = http://www.tv.com/star-jones/september-18-2007/episode/1139367/summary.html?tag=ep_guide;summary }}</ref> ''Best Defense'' with [[Jami Floyd]] and ''Courtside'' with [[Ashley Banfield]] and [[Jack Ford (news anchor)|Jack Ford]] where he primarily offered day-to-day coverage on O.J. Simpson's kidnapping trial.<ref>Friess, Steve The New York Times September 15, 2008 [https://www.nytimes.com/2008/09/15/world/americas/15iht-simpson.4.16177191.html O.J. Simpson once acquitted of murder, now on trial for robbery, kidnapping]</ref>\n\n===Thad Aubert===\nWhile on its face an insignificant case of first degree case kidnapping and robbery with use a deadly weapon, it was during this trial that Figler and his frequent co-counsel, Daniel M. Bunin, brought to light a long-standing practice of the Clark County District Attorney's office of compensating witnesses for appearing in their private offices.  Causing a controversy within the legal community that is ongoing,<ref>\n{{Citation\n| last = Barnes\n| first = Bethany\n| title = Defense attorneys cry foul\n| newspaper = Las Vegas Sun\n| location = Las Vegas, Nevada\n| date =  13 October 2009\n| url= http://www.lasvegassun.com/news/2013/oct/13/defense-attorneys-cry-foul-over-da-paying-witnesse/}}</ref> the footnote to the case is that Figler and Bunin were able to secure a full acquittal from the jury after only 15 minutes of deliberation.<ref>\n{{Citation\n| last = Goldman\n| first = Abigail\n| title = Controversy erupts over prosecutors paying witnesses...\n| newspaper = Las Vegas Sun\n| location = Las Vegas, Nevada\n| date = 13 February 2009\n| url= http://www.lasvegassun.com/news/2009/feb/13/revelation-prosecutors-have-paid-witnesses-stirs-c/ }}</ref> In the case of Gary Miller some four years later, the issue was raised again by Figler and Bunin, and again they secured a full acquittal of 20 felony counts of sexual assault.  The District Attorney announced that after 20 years of doing it, they were ending this \"inappropriate\" practice.\n\n==Radio, writing and arts==\nBeginning with the first of two Fellowships from the Nevada State Council for the Arts in 1997 for performance poetry (the other came in 2001 for fiction),<ref>\n{{Cite press release\n  | title =  Nevada Arts Council Fellowship Recipients\n  | publisher = Nevada Arts Council\n  | date = 2001-01-01\n  | url = http://nevadaculture.org/nac/index.php?option=com_content&task=view&id=1316&Itemid=367\n  | accessdate = 2010-01-10}}</ref> Figler has embarked upon a creative life to run parallel with his law career.   (He is the only multiple Fellowship winner in two distinct categories).\n\nA popular Nevada (former) [[slam poet]] and travelling urban storyteller, Figler has toured the United States at many festivals and events as a featured performer.\n.<ref>{{Citation\n  | last = Abowitz\n  | first = Richard\n  | title = A mix of messages from a voice in the desert\n  | newspaper = The Los Angeles Times\n  | location = Los Angeles, California\n  | date = 14 May 2006\n  | url = http://articles.latimes.com/2006/may/14/entertainment/ca-vegas14 }}</ref> Most notably, since 1997, he has been featured at SxSW, Bumbershoot,<ref>\n{{Citation\n  | last = Staff\n  | first = Writer\n  | title = Bumbershoot Readers\n  | newspaper = The Seattle Weekly\n  | location = Seattle, WA\n  | date = 25 August 1999\n  | url = http://www.seattleweekly.com/1999-08-25/arts/bumbershoot-reg-readings-panel-discussions-bookarts-signings-poetry-slam-poetry-championship-bout-starbucks-bookfair-open-mike/}}</ref> North by Northwest, the National Poetry Slam competition, the Porchlight storytelling series in San Francisco,<ref>{{Citation\n  | last = Palevsky\n  | first = Stacey\n  | title = Storytelling series sinks its teeth into Jewish food\n  | newspaper = jWeekly\n  | location = San Francisco, California\n  | date = 11 April 2008\n  | url =  http://www.jweekly.com/article/full/34721/storytelling-series-sinks-its-teeth-into-jewish-food/}}</ref> the Back Fence PDX storytelling series in Portland, Oregon,<ref>{{cite web|author=8 years ago |url=http://vimeo.com/4889641 |title=Dayvid Figler at Back Fence PDX on Vimeo |website=Vimeo.com |date=2009-05-28 |accessdate=2017-06-30}}</ref> HEEB storytelling and the [[SF Sketchfest]] 2011 & 2012.  In Nevada, he tours as part of the Tumblewords initiative through the Nevada Arts Council bringing literary events to rural Nevada towns.   In 1998, he created a one-man show called \u201cDayvid Figler IS Jim Morrison in Hello I Love You, Where You Folks From?\u201d.<ref>{{Citation\n  | last = Dickensheets\n  | first = Scott\n  | title = Re-Light My Fire\n  | newspaper = Las Vegas Sun\n  | location = Las Vegas, NV\n  | date = 20 October 1998\n  | url = http://www.lasvegassun.com/news/1998/oct/20/re-light-my-fire/ }}</ref> In 2006, he was named Best Las Vegas Poet by the readers of LV CityLife weekly.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.lasvegascitylife.com/articles/2006/11/16/news/cover/iq_10736085.txt |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2009-09-20 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://archive.is/20120908132458/http://www.lasvegascitylife.com/articles/2006/11/16/news/cover/iq_10736085.txt |archivedate=2012-09-08 }}</ref>\nIn October 2010, Figler took his storytelling experiences further by producing Las Vegas' premier storytelling series, The Tell.<ref>{{cite web|last=Staff |first=Seven |url=http://vegasseven.com/2012/07/30/tell-storytellers-set/ |title=The Tell Storytellers Set |publisher=Vegas Seven |date=2012-07-30 |accessdate=2017-06-30}}</ref>\n\nIn 2000, he began as a featured commentator on radio station, KNPR in Las Vegas and his audio essays are archived under the banner \u201cAin\u2019t Necessarily So\u201d on the station's website.  A number of those commentaries were broadcast nationally on NPR's [[All Things Considered]].  In 2002, 2003 and then again in 2005, his essays were named Best Radio Program by the Electronic Media Awards, Las Vegas\u2019 primary broadcast media awards.<ref>{{cite web|last=Meehan |first=Jeffrey |url=http://www.lvbusinesspress.com/articles/2005/11/07/news/onthemove.txt |title=Las Vegas Business Press \u2013 Las Vegas Business Press |website=Lvbusinesspress.com |date= |accessdate=2017-06-30}}</ref>  In 2003, he was also named Best Radio Personality by reader's poll of the [[Las Vegas Review Journal]], Nevada's largest circulation daily paper.<ref>{{cite web|last=Corder |first=Mike |url=http://www.reviewjournal.com/bestoflv/2003/LongReturns.jsp?bestID=3893 |title=Las Vegas Review-Journal \u2013 The most reliable source for Las Vegas news, breaking news |website=Reviewjournal.com |date= |accessdate=2017-06-30}}</ref> In 2010, the Vegas Valley Book Festival awarded the individual Crystal Bookmark Award to Figler for his lifelong contribution to the cause of literary awareness in Southern Nevada.\n\nA frequent contributor to Las Vegas weekly and monthly magazines, his first national magazine article was the main feature for the Politics issue of [[Heeb (magazine)]], where he profiled (former) Las Vegas Mayor Oscar Goodman and he's since taken up writing legal creative non-fiction for nsfwcorp.<ref>\n\n{{Citation\n |last        = Figler\n |first       = Dayvid\n |title       = The First Jewish President\n |newspaper   = Heeb Magazine\n |location    = New York, NY\n |date        = 1 October 2008\n |url         = http://www.heebmagazine.com/articles/view/159\n |url-status     = dead\n |archiveurl  = https://web.archive.org/web/20090908171624/http://www.heebmagazine.com/articles/view/159\n |archivedate = 8 September 2009\n}} ]</ref>\n\nIn 2005, Portland small press, Future Tense, published his short fictional work of humor, GROPE, about two Las Vegas natives finding a connection in a strip club.  Figler is a contributor to Las Vegas guidebooks, including Time Out and also has stories or poems in a number of anthologies including In the Shadow of the Strip (University of Nevada Press), Literary Nevada (University of Nevada Press), The Perpetual Engine of Hope (CityLife Books) Poetry Slam (Manic D Press) and Nevada: 150 years in the Silver State (University of Nevada Press).<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.amazon.com/s/ref=nb_ss?url=search-alias%3Dstripbooks&field-keywords=dayvid+figler&x=0&y=0 |title=dayvid figler: Books |website=Amazon.com |date=2017-06-14 |accessdate=2017-06-30}}</ref>\n\nRumors abound of a reunion of the seminal \u201cgoofcore\u201d punk rock polka band, Tippy Elvis, where Figler served as lead vocalist and primary lyricist.<ref>\n\n{{Citation\n  | last = Dickensheets\n  | first = Scott\n  | title = Go Figler!\n  | newspaper = Las Vegas Sun\n  | location = Las Vegas, NV\n  | date = 15 July 1996\n  | url = http://www.lasvegassun.com/news/1996/jul/15/go-figler/ }}</ref> Popular in Las Vegas in the mid-90s, the band did reunite for one show as a surprise to Figler on his 40th birthday and a second show in 2011 at the Artifice bar as part of the Neon Reverb Music Festival.<ref>{{Citation\n  | last = Seabaugh\n  | first = Julie\n  | title = Tippy Elvis Reunites\n  | newspaper = Las Vegas Weekly\n  | location = Las Vegas, NV\n  | date = 22 Aug 2007\n  | url = http://www.lasvegasweekly.com/news/archive/2007/aug/22/flip-side-tippy-elvis-reunites/}}</ref> During its heyday, Tippy Elvis was an opening act for [[Mojo Nixon]], [[Boiled in Lead]] and [[Idiot Flesh]].\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.knpr.org/aint/listNEW.cfm KNPR archive]\n*[http://www.nsfwcorp.com/author/dayvid-figler/ NSFWcorp author page]\n*[http://www.myspace.com/tippyelvis TIPPY ELVIS Myspace Page]\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Figler, Dayvid}}\n[[Category:1967 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:American male writers]]\n[[Category:Lawyers from Chicago]]\n[[Category:People from the Las Vegas Valley]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|American lawyer}}\n'''Dayvid Figler''' (born August 18, 1967, [[Chicago]], [[Illinois]], United States) is an American performer, author and trial [[lawyer]].  He became one of the youngest lawyers in [[Nevada]] history after successfully taking the bar exam at age 23. In 2003, he began and served a short term as a [[Las Vegas, Nevada|Las Vegas]] municipal court judge after being appointed by Mayor [[Oscar B. Goodman]].<ref>\n{{Citation\n  | last =  \n  | first = \n  | title = The Show Goes on at Municipal Court...\n  | newspaper = The Las Vegas Sun\n  | location = Las Vegas, Nevada\n  | date = 9 January 2003\n  | url = http://www.lasvegassun.com/news/2003/jan/09/the-show-goes-on-at-municipal-court/}}</ref>\nApart from his success as one of the better known criminal defense attorneys in Las Vegas, he has become a regarded legal commentator, one of the most quoted authorities on Las Vegas,<ref>{{Citation\n  | last =  Deutsch\n  | first = Linda\n  | title = Simpson's Future Now Hangs...\n  | newspaper = USA Today\n  | location = Washington, D.C.\n  | date = 7 October 2008\n  | url = http://www.lasvegassun.com/search/?q=figler&author=&from=&to=&sortby=dateand}}</ref>\nand a prolific radio commentator and writer on a variety of topics related to Las Vegas.<ref>\n{{Citation\n | people = Ain't Necessarily So\n | title = KNPR radio\n | url = http://www.knpr.org\n | medium = Radio-Program\n | publisher = Ain't Necessarily So\n | location = Las Vegas, Nevada\n | accessdate =2017-06-30 }}\n</ref>\n\n==Background==\nFigler graduated from the [[University of the Pacific (United States)|University of the Pacific]] \u2013 [[McGeorge School of Law]] in 1991. At McGeorge he served as Student Body President.  He started his career in his hometown of Las Vegas, where his family relocated in 1971.  Raised in Las Vegas, his unique perspective as a so-called \u201cVegas kid\u201d has produced numerous humor oriented anecdotes which have provided the fodder for hundreds of radio essays which have appeared on Las Vegas National Public Radio affiliate, [[KNPR]], as well as [[NPR]]\u2019s [[All Things Considered]] Program.  He is also an alum of one of the longest running sketch college sketch comedy groups in the nation, [[Comedy Corner]] at the University of Arizona. In 2019, he was awarded the prestigious Medal of Justice honor from the Nevada State Bar.<ref>{{Citation | date = 6 May 2019 | url=https://www.nvbar.org/state-bar-of-nevada-announces-recipients-of-the-2019-membership-awards/|title=State Bar of Nevada Announces Recipients of the 2019 Membership Awards}}</ref>\n\nDayvid Figler served as a congressional intern in Washington, D.C. for now Senate Majority Leader [[Harry M. Reid]] in 1987 and later  completed an internship with the United States Attorneys office in Las Vegas. Upon graduation from law school, he worked for a number of unions and fellow high-profile criminal defense attorney, Dominic Gentile.  Eventually, Figler took an associate position with the Clark County Special Public Defender's office where he exclusively represented indigents charged with murder, including those facing the [[death penalty]].  It is in this office where he began a professional relationship with noted Las Vegas attorney, Kristina Wildeveld that continues to this day.\n\nHe has been cited and quoted as a noted legal expert in many places including the New York Times, National Public Radio, Newsweek, USA Today and the Los Angeles Times.<ref>{{Citation\n  | last = Friess\n  | first = Steve\n  | title = After apologies, Simpson is sentenced...\n  | newspaper = The New York Times\n  | location = New York\n  | date = 6 December 2008\n  | url = https://www.nytimes.com/2008/12/06/us/06simpson.html?scp=9&sq=figler&st=cse }}</ref><ref>{{Citation\n  | last = Robbins\n  | first = Ted\n  | title = O.J. Simpson to be sentenced...\n  | newspaper = National Public Radio\n  | date = 5 December 2008\n  | url =https://www.npr.org/templates/story/story.php?storyId=97843646 }}</ref><ref>{{Citation\n |last=Abowitz \n |first=Richard \n |title=One former Vegas judge on \"juice\"... \n |newspaper=The Los Angeles Times \n |location=Los Angeles, California \n |date=2006-06-13 \n |url=http://vegasblog.latimes.com/vegas/2006/06/one_former_vega.html \n |url-status=dead \n |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110713191421/http://vegasblog.latimes.com/vegas/2006/06/one_former_vega.html \n |archivedate=2011-07-13 \n}}</ref>\n\n==High profile cases==\n===Donte Johnson===\nFigler's first case of note was defending against the death penalty prosecution of Donte Johnson, a California gang member who directed the kidnapping and execution style murders of four young men in Las Vegas in 1998.  The four young men were followers of the band, [[Phish]], and the stated motive for their killing was an attempt to steal money the men had made on the road with Phish.  At trial, evidence was presented that Johnson was responsible for a number of other murders and attempt murders.  The jury, however, did not impose the death penalty after Figler's impassioned closing argument. Later, a 3-judge panel of judges imposed the death penalty.  Arguing one of the first cases in the country in light of the U.S. Supreme Court's 2000 ruling in [[Apprendi v. New Jersey]], Figler successfully advocated the landmark case and in a published opinion, the 3-judge death panels of Nevada were ruled unconstitutional and the Court vacated the imposition of the death penalty.  JOHNSON V. STATE, 118 Nev. Adv. Op. No. 79 (12/18/02)<ref>\n{{Cite court\n  |litigants=Johnson v. State\n  |vol=118\n  |reporter=Nev. Adv. Op.\n  |opinion=79\n  |pinpoint=\n  |court= Nevada Supreme Court\n  |date=2002\n  |url=http://www.nvbar.org/nevada_lawyer_articles3.asp?ID=195 }}</ref>\n\n===Gloria Guzman===\n\nAs a lawyer, Figler was first showcased before a national audience on CourtTV (later TruTV) after the gavel-to-gavel coverage of the trial of Gloria Guzman in 2006.  There, Guzman was a nurse caretaker who fell in love with and married one of her charges in a facility who was also a quadriplegic.  The two moved out of the facility and into an apartment where they engaged in a destructive lifestyle involving methamphetamine and guns. When her husband drowned in a bathtub, Guzman was accused of first degree murder.  Midtrial, Figler discovered that the police had falsified the transcript of her confession and a hasty plea bargain later the previously incarcerated Guzman was given credit for time served.  This case marked the first of numerous appearances for Figler on the [[Nancy Grace]] program both as a guest and a commentator.<ref>Nancy Grace, CNN Headline News, [http://transcripts.cnn.com/TRANSCRIPTS/0608/14/ng.01.html  Plea Deal in Nevada]</ref>  The Nancy Grace appearances led to a number of guest appearances on other TruTV programs including [[Star Jones]],<ref>\n{{Citation\n  | last = Jones\n  | first = Star\n  | title = The Star Jones Program\n  | newspaper = Star Jones\n  | location = New York\n  | date = 18 September 2007\n  | url = http://www.tv.com/star-jones/september-18-2007/episode/1139367/summary.html?tag=ep_guide;summary }}</ref> ''Best Defense'' with [[Jami Floyd]] and ''Courtside'' with [[Ashley Banfield]] and [[Jack Ford (news anchor)|Jack Ford]] where he primarily offered day-to-day coverage on O.J. Simpson's kidnapping trial.<ref>Friess, Steve The New York Times September 15, 2008 [https://www.nytimes.com/2008/09/15/world/americas/15iht-simpson.4.16177191.html O.J. Simpson once acquitted of murder, now on trial for robbery, kidnapping]</ref>\n\n===Thad Aubert===\nWhile on its face an insignificant case of first degree case kidnapping and robbery with use a deadly weapon, it was during this trial that Figler and his frequent co-counsel, Daniel M. Bunin, brought to light a long-standing practice of the Clark County District Attorney's office of compensating witnesses for appearing in their private offices.  Causing a controversy within the legal community that is ongoing,<ref>\n{{Citation\n| last = Barnes\n| first = Bethany\n| title = Defense attorneys cry foul\n| newspaper = Las Vegas Sun\n| location = Las Vegas, Nevada\n| date =  13 October 2009\n| url= http://www.lasvegassun.com/news/2013/oct/13/defense-attorneys-cry-foul-over-da-paying-witnesse/}}</ref> the footnote to the case is that Figler and Bunin were able to secure a full acquittal from the jury after only 15 minutes of deliberation.<ref>\n{{Citation\n| last = Goldman\n| first = Abigail\n| title = Controversy erupts over prosecutors paying witnesses...\n| newspaper = Las Vegas Sun\n| location = Las Vegas, Nevada\n| date = 13 February 2009\n| url= http://www.lasvegassun.com/news/2009/feb/13/revelation-prosecutors-have-paid-witnesses-stirs-c/ }}</ref> In the case of Gary Miller some four years later, the issue was raised again by Figler and Bunin, and again they secured a full acquittal of 20 felony counts of sexual assault.  The District Attorney announced that after 20 years of doing it, they were ending this \"inappropriate\" practice.\n\n==Radio, writing and arts==\nBeginning with the first of two Fellowships from the Nevada State Council for the Arts in 1997 for performance poetry (the other came in 2001 for fiction),<ref>\n{{Cite press release\n  | title =  Nevada Arts Council Fellowship Recipients\n  | publisher = Nevada Arts Council\n  | date = 2001-01-01\n  | url = http://nevadaculture.org/nac/index.php?option=com_content&task=view&id=1316&Itemid=367\n  | accessdate = 2010-01-10}}</ref> Figler has embarked upon a creative life to run parallel with his law career.   (He is the only multiple Fellowship winner in two distinct categories).\n\nA popular Nevada (former) [[slam poet]] and travelling urban storyteller, Figler has toured the United States at many festivals and events as a featured performer.\n.<ref>{{Citation\n  | last = Abowitz\n  | first = Richard\n  | title = A mix of messages from a voice in the desert\n  | newspaper = The Los Angeles Times\n  | location = Los Angeles, California\n  | date = 14 May 2006\n  | url = http://articles.latimes.com/2006/may/14/entertainment/ca-vegas14 }}</ref> Most notably, since 1997, he has been featured at SxSW, Bumbershoot,<ref>\n{{Citation\n  | last = Staff\n  | first = Writer\n  | title = Bumbershoot Readers\n  | newspaper = The Seattle Weekly\n  | location = Seattle, WA\n  | date = 25 August 1999\n  | url = http://www.seattleweekly.com/1999-08-25/arts/bumbershoot-reg-readings-panel-discussions-bookarts-signings-poetry-slam-poetry-championship-bout-starbucks-bookfair-open-mike/}}</ref> North by Northwest, the National Poetry Slam competition, the Porchlight storytelling series in San Francisco,<ref>{{Citation\n  | last = Palevsky\n  | first = Stacey\n  | title = Storytelling series sinks its teeth into Jewish food\n  | newspaper = jWeekly\n  | location = San Francisco, California\n  | date = 11 April 2008\n  | url =  http://www.jweekly.com/article/full/34721/storytelling-series-sinks-its-teeth-into-jewish-food/}}</ref> the Back Fence PDX storytelling series in Portland, Oregon,<ref>{{cite web|author=8 years ago |url=http://vimeo.com/4889641 |title=Dayvid Figler at Back Fence PDX on Vimeo |website=Vimeo.com |date=2009-05-28 |accessdate=2017-06-30}}</ref> HEEB storytelling and the [[SF Sketchfest]] 2011 & 2012.  In Nevada, he tours as part of the Tumblewords initiative through the Nevada Arts Council bringing literary events to rural Nevada towns.   In 1998, he created a one-man show called \u201cDayvid Figler IS Jim Morrison in Hello I Love You, Where You Folks From?\u201d.<ref>{{Citation\n  | last = Dickensheets\n  | first = Scott\n  | title = Re-Light My Fire\n  | newspaper = Las Vegas Sun\n  | location = Las Vegas, NV\n  | date = 20 October 1998\n  | url = http://www.lasvegassun.com/news/1998/oct/20/re-light-my-fire/ }}</ref> In 2006, he was named Best Las Vegas Poet by the readers of LV CityLife weekly.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.lasvegascitylife.com/articles/2006/11/16/news/cover/iq_10736085.txt |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2009-09-20 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://archive.is/20120908132458/http://www.lasvegascitylife.com/articles/2006/11/16/news/cover/iq_10736085.txt |archivedate=2012-09-08 }}</ref>\nIn October 2010, Figler took his storytelling experiences further by producing Las Vegas' premier storytelling series, The Tell.<ref>{{cite web|last=Staff |first=Seven |url=http://vegasseven.com/2012/07/30/tell-storytellers-set/ |title=The Tell Storytellers Set |publisher=Vegas Seven |date=2012-07-30 |accessdate=2017-06-30}}</ref>\n\nIn 2000, he began as a featured commentator on radio station, KNPR in Las Vegas and his audio essays are archived under the banner \u201cAin\u2019t Necessarily So\u201d on the station's website.  A number of those commentaries were broadcast nationally on NPR's [[All Things Considered]].  In 2002, 2003 and then again in 2005, his essays were named Best Radio Program by the Electronic Media Awards, Las Vegas\u2019 primary broadcast media awards.<ref>{{cite web|last=Meehan |first=Jeffrey |url=http://www.lvbusinesspress.com/articles/2005/11/07/news/onthemove.txt |title=Las Vegas Business Press \u2013 Las Vegas Business Press |website=Lvbusinesspress.com |date= |accessdate=2017-06-30}}</ref>  In 2003, he was also named Best Radio Personality by reader's poll of the [[Las Vegas Review Journal]], Nevada's largest circulation daily paper.<ref>{{cite web|last=Corder |first=Mike |url=http://www.reviewjournal.com/bestoflv/2003/LongReturns.jsp?bestID=3893 |title=Las Vegas Review-Journal \u2013 The most reliable source for Las Vegas news, breaking news |website=Reviewjournal.com |date= |accessdate=2017-06-30}}</ref> In 2010, the Vegas Valley Book Festival awarded the individual Crystal Bookmark Award to Figler for his lifelong contribution to the cause of literary awareness in Southern Nevada.\n\nA frequent contributor to Las Vegas weekly and monthly magazines, his first national magazine article was the main feature for the Politics issue of [[Heeb (magazine)]], where he profiled (former) Las Vegas Mayor Oscar Goodman and he's since taken up writing legal creative non-fiction for nsfwcorp.<ref>\n\n{{Citation\n |last        = Figler\n |first       = Dayvid\n |title       = The First Jewish President\n |newspaper   = Heeb Magazine\n |location    = New York, NY\n |date        = 1 October 2008\n |url         = http://www.heebmagazine.com/articles/view/159\n |url-status     = dead\n |archiveurl  = https://web.archive.org/web/20090908171624/http://www.heebmagazine.com/articles/view/159\n |archivedate = 8 September 2009\n}} ]</ref>\n\nIn 2005, Portland small press, Future Tense, published his short fictional work of humor, GROPE, about two Las Vegas natives finding a connection in a strip club.  Figler is a contributor to Las Vegas guidebooks, including Time Out and also has stories or poems in a number of anthologies including In the Shadow of the Strip (University of Nevada Press), Literary Nevada (University of Nevada Press), The Perpetual Engine of Hope (CityLife Books) Poetry Slam (Manic D Press) and Nevada: 150 years in the Silver State (University of Nevada Press).<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.amazon.com/s/ref=nb_ss?url=search-alias%3Dstripbooks&field-keywords=dayvid+figler&x=0&y=0 |title=dayvid figler: Books |website=Amazon.com |date=2017-06-14 |accessdate=2017-06-30}}</ref>\n\nRumors abound of a reunion of the seminal \u201cgoofcore\u201d punk rock polka band, Tippy Elvis, where Figler served as lead vocalist and primary lyricist.<ref>\n\n{{Citation\n  | last = Dickensheets\n  | first = Scott\n  | title = Go Figler!\n  | newspaper = Las Vegas Sun\n  | location = Las Vegas, NV\n  | date = 15 July 1996\n  | url = http://www.lasvegassun.com/news/1996/jul/15/go-figler/ }}</ref> Popular in Las Vegas in the mid-90s, the band did reunite for one show as a surprise to Figler on his 40th birthday and a second show in 2011 at the Artifice bar as part of the Neon Reverb Music Festival.<ref>{{Citation\n  | last = Seabaugh\n  | first = Julie\n  | title = Tippy Elvis Reunites\n  | newspaper = Las Vegas Weekly\n  | location = Las Vegas, NV\n  | date = 22 Aug 2007\n  | url = http://www.lasvegasweekly.com/news/archive/2007/aug/22/flip-side-tippy-elvis-reunites/}}</ref> During its heyday, Tippy Elvis was an opening act for [[Mojo Nixon]], [[Boiled in Lead]] and [[Idiot Flesh]].\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.knpr.org/aint/listNEW.cfm KNPR archive]\n*[http://www.nsfwcorp.com/author/dayvid-figler/ NSFWcorp author page]\n*[http://www.myspace.com/tippyelvis TIPPY ELVIS Myspace Page]\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Figler, Dayvid}}\n[[Category:1967 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:American male writers]]\n[[Category:Lawyers from Chicago]]\n[[Category:People from the Las Vegas Valley]]\n", "name_user": "Chris the speller", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eBackground:replaced: Student Body President \u2192 student body president", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Dayvid_Figler"}
{"title_page": "The Marin School", "text_new": "{{pp-pc1}}\n{{Infobox School\n|name              = The Marin School\n|native_name       = \n|latin_name        = \n|logo              = MarinSchoollogo.png\n|image             = The Marin School - July 2016.jpg\n|imagesize         = \n|caption           = \n|location          = \n|streetaddress     = 150 N. San Pedro Road\n|affiliations      = \n|city              = [[San Rafael, California|San Rafael]] \n|state             = [[California]]\n|county            = [[Marin County]]\n|zipcode           = 94903\n|country           = [[United States]]\n|country1          = \n|coordinates       = {{Coor title dms|37|59|56.01|N|122|31|27.27|W|scale:6250_region:US}}\n|schoolnumber      = \n|schoolboard       = \n|district          = \n|authority         = \n|chairperson       = \n|principal         = Barbra J Brown, EdD\n|staff             = \n|ranking           = \n|faculty           = \n|teaching_staff    = \n|ratio             = 7:1\n|testaverage       = \n|testname          = \n|national_ranking  = \n|avg_class_size    = \n|type              = [[Private school|Private]] \n|grades            = 9-12\n|classrooms        = \n|campus            = \n|campus size       = \n|campus type       = \n|motto             = Small School, Big Impact.\n|accreditation     = Western Association of Schools and Colleges (WASC)\n|mascot            = Nighthawks\n|mascot image      = \n|sports            =Soccer, Basketball, and Track \n|team_name         = \n|nickname          =TMS \n|school_colors     = Green and Black\n|yearbook          = \n|publication       = \n|newspaper         = \n|opened            = \n|established       = 1980\n|founded           = \n|status            = \n|closed            = \n|students          = 85\n|enrollment        = \n|grade9            = \n|grade10           = \n|grade11           = \n|grade12           = \n|grade13           = \n|communities       = \n|feeders           = \n|free_label        = \n|free_text         = \n|free_label1       = \n|free_text1        = \n|free_label2       = \n|free_text2        = \n|picture           = \n|homepage          = [http://www.themarinschool.org/ TheMarinSchool.org]\n}}\n\n'''The Marin School''' (TMS) is a [[Private school|private high school]] located in [[San Rafael, California]]. The school is named after [[Marin County]] in which it is located.<ref>[http://www.themarinschool.org/index.html The Marin School], accessed 02-05-2009</ref><ref>[http://www.privateschoolreview.com/school_ov/school_id/3167 Private School Review], accessed 02-05-2009</ref><ref>[http://projects.latimes.com/schools/school/sausalito/marin-school-the/] [[Los Angeles Times]], accessed 02-05-2009</ref>\n\n==History==\nThe Marin School, formerly known as North Bay Secondary School then as North Bay Marin School, was founded in 1980 and originally included both a middle school and high school.  The school accepted a wide range of students with varying levels of creativity, academic ability, and motivation. The school was characterized by small classes, close monitoring, and personalized attention given to each individual.<ref name=OA>[http://www.orindaacademy.org/welcome/our-history Orinda Academy], \"Our History\", accessed 02-05-2009</ref>\n\n====Two Schools====\nIn the mid 1980s, the North Bay Marin School split into two schools (North Bay Marin School<ref name=\"CSO\">[http://california.schooltree.org/private/North-Bay-Marin-004903.html california.schooltree.org], North Bay Marin School, accessed 03-05-2009</ref>  and North Bay [[Orinda, California|Orinda]] School (now known as [[Orinda Academy]])), but remained a single corporation with a single Board of Directors.<ref name=\"OA\" /> In 1995, the former Head resigned, and the Board of Directors asked Barbara Schakel (a part-time English teacher hired in 1989) to assume the responsibilities of Head of School. In 1998, the North Bay Marin School legally separated from the [[Orinda Academy|North Bay Orinda School]], established a separate non-profit corporation, and created a new Board of Directors.<ref name=\"OA\" />\n\n====Transformation====\nThe Marin School, formerly classified as an [[alternative school]], transformed into a [[college-preparatory]] school. The school's unique schedule of alternating tradition classroom education and a discussion workshop remained a key feature of the educational program. Barbara J. Brown, EdD, appointed at the beginning of the school year 2011\u20132012, is now Head of School.<ref>[http://www.themarinschool.org/about/about_unique.html The Marin School, Unique], accessed 02-05-2009</ref>\n\n==Curriculum==\nIn recent years, The Marin School has expanded its curricular offerings and now has a strong focus in [[technology]] and the [[arts]]. The school continues to offer small classes, individualized attention, experiential opportunities and an online tracking system that includes daily assignments, biweekly grade updates and daily progress statistics. The \u201cOutside the Walls\u201d program, a series of curriculum-related field trips, is designed to give students a real-world application of their classroom.<ref>[http://www.themarinschool.org/curriculum/curriculum.htm The Marin School, Curriculum], accessed 02-05-2009</ref>\n\n==Enrollment==\nThe school continues to enroll students with varied interests, learning styles and abilities from different socio-economic backgrounds.  The school also supports 18% of its student body with financial assistance. The Marin School offers small classes with an average of eight students, a small student/teacher ratio, an experiential college-preparatory curriculum, and a focus on the individual.<ref>[http://www.themarinschool.org/admissions/adm_financial.htm The Marin School, Financial], accessed 02-05-2009</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.themarinschool.org/ The Marin School website]\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Marin School}}\n[[Category:High schools in Marin County, California]]\n[[Category:Private high schools in California]]\n[[Category:Preparatory schools in California]]\n", "text_old": "{{pp-pc1}}\n{{Infobox School\n|name              = The Marin School\n|native_name       = \n|latin_name        = \n|logo              = MarinSchoollogo.png\n|image             = The Marin School - July 2016.jpg\n|imagesize         = \n|caption           = \n|location          = \n|streetaddress     = 150 N. San Pedro Road\n|affiliations      = \n|city              = [[San Rafael, California|San Rafael]] \n|state             = [[California]]\n|county            = [[Marin County]]\n|zipcode           = 94903\n|country           = [[United States]]\n|country1          = \n|coordinates       = {{Coor title dms|37|59|56.01|N|122|31|27.27|W|scale:6250_region:US}}\n|schoolnumber      = \n|schoolboard       = \n|district          = \n|authority         = \n|chairperson       = \n|principal         = Barbra J Brown, EdD\n|staff             = \n|ranking           = \n|faculty           = \n|teaching_staff    = \n|ratio             = 7:1\n|testaverage       = \n|testname          = \n|national_ranking  = \n|avg_class_size    = \n|type              = [[Private school|Private]] \n|grades            = 9-12\n|classrooms        = \n|campus            = \n|campus size       = \n|campus type       = \n|motto             = Small School, Big Impact.\n|accreditation     = Western Association of Schools and Colleges (WASC)\n|mascot            = Nighthawks\n|mascot image      = \n|sports            =Soccer, Basketball, and Track \n|team_name         = \n|nickname          =TMS \n|school_colors     = Green and Black\n|yearbook          = \n|publication       = \n|newspaper         = \n|opened            = \n|established       = 1980\n|founded           = \n|status            = \n|closed            = \n|students          = 85\n|enrollment        = \n|grade9            = \n|grade10           = \n|grade11           = \n|grade12           = \n|grade13           = \n|communities       = \n|feeders           = \n|free_label        = \n|free_text         = \n|free_label1       = \n|free_text1        = \n|free_label2       = \n|free_text2        = \n|picture           = \n|homepage          = [http://www.themarinschool.org/ TheMarinSchool.org]\n}}\n\n'''The Marin School''' (TMS) is a [[Private school|private high school]] located in [[San Rafael, California]]. The school is named after [[Marin County]] in which it is located.<ref>[http://www.themarinschool.org/index.html The Marin School], accessed 02-05-2009</ref><ref>[http://www.privateschoolreview.com/school_ov/school_id/3167 Private School Review], accessed 02-05-2009</ref><ref>[http://projects.latimes.com/schools/school/sausalito/marin-school-the/] [[Los Angeles Times]], accessed 02-05-2009</ref>\n\n==History==\nThe Marin School, formerly known as North Bay Secondary School then as North Bay Marin School, was founded in 1980 and originally included both a middle school and high school.  The school accepted a wide range of students with varying levels of creativity, academic ability, and motivation. The school was characterized by small classes, close monitoring, and personalized attention given to each individual.<ref name=OA>[http://www.orindaacademy.org/welcome/our-history Orinda Academy], \"Our History\", accessed 02-05-2009</ref>\n\n==Two Schools==\nIn the mid 1980s, the North Bay Marin School split into two schools (North Bay Marin School<ref name=CSO>[http://california.schooltree.org/private/North-Bay-Marin-004903.html california.schooltree.org], North Bay Marin School, accessed 03-05-2009</ref>  and North Bay [[Orinda, California|Orinda]] School (now known as [[Orinda Academy]])<ref name=OA/>), but remained a single corporation with a single Board of Directors. In 1995, the former Head resigned, and the Board of Directors asked Barbara Schakel (a part-time English teacher hired in 1989) to assume the responsibilities of Head of School. In 1998, the North Bay Marin School legally separated from the North Bay Orinda School, established a separate non-profit corporation, and created a new Board of Directors.<ref name=OA/>\n\n==Transformation==\nThe Marin School, formerly classified as an [[alternative school]], transformed into a [[college-preparatory]] school. The school's unique schedule of alternating tradition classroom education and a discussion workshop remained a key feature of the educational program. Barbara J. Brown, EdD, appointed at the beginning of the school year 2011/12, is now Head of School.<ref>[http://www.themarinschool.org/about/about_unique.html The Marin School, Unique], accessed 02-05-2009</ref>\n\n==Curriculum==\nIn recent years, '''The Marin School''' has expanded its curricular offerings and now has a strong focus in [[technology]] and the [[arts]]. Classes are interactive and workshops allow teachers and students to review homework and check for understanding. The school continues to offer small classes, individualized attention, experiential opportunities and an online tracking system that includes daily assignments, biweekly grade updates and daily progress statistics. The \u201cOutside the Walls\u201d program, a series of curriculum-related field trips, is designed to give students a real-world application of their classroom.<ref>[http://www.themarinschool.org/curriculum/curriculum.htm The Marin School, Curriculum], accessed 02-05-2009</ref>\n\n==Enrollment==\nThe school continues to enroll students with varied interests, learning styles and abilities from different socio-economic backgrounds.  The school also supports 18% of its student body with financial assistance. '''The Marin School''' offers small classes with an average of eight students, a small student/teacher ratio, an experiential college-preparatory curriculum, and a focus on the individual.\n<ref>[http://www.themarinschool.org/admissions/adm_financial.htm The Marin School, Financial], accessed 02-05-2009</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.themarinschool.org/ The Marin School website]\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Marin School}}\n[[Category:High schools in Marin County, California]]\n[[Category:Private high schools in California]]\n[[Category:Preparatory schools in California]]\n", "name_user": "KidAd", "label": "safe", "comment": "structuring", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/The_Marin_School"}
{"title_page": "Steve Cooley", "text_new": "{{short description|American politician and prosecutor|bot=PearBOT 5}}\n{{Update|inaccurate=yes|date=October 2012}}\n{{Infobox officeholder\n|name        = Steve Cooley\n|image       = Steve Cooley cropped flipped.jpg\n|office      = 41st [[Los Angeles County District Attorney|District Attorney of Los Angeles County]]\n|term_start  = December 4, 2000<ref>{{cite web |url=http://articles.latimes.com/2000/dec/04/local/me-60941 |title=For New District Attorney, Reality Check Begins Today |work=The Los Angeles Times |author=Mitchell Landsberg |date=December 4, 2000 |accessdate=December 1, 2018}}</ref>\n|term_end    = December 3, 2012\n|predecessor = [[Gil Garcetti]]\n|successor   = [[Jackie Lacey]]\n|party       = [[Republican Party (United States)|Republican]]\n|birth_name  = Stephen Lawrence Cooley\n|birth_date  = {{birth date and age|1947|5|1}}\n|birth_place = [[Los Angeles, California]], U.S.\n|occupation  = Criminal prosecutor\n|alma_mater  = [[California State University, Los Angeles]]<br />[[USC Gould School of Law]]\n|spouse      = {{marriage|Jana Cooley|1975}}\n|children    = 2\n|website     = [http://www.stevecooley.com/ Official website]\n}}\n\n'''Stephen Lawrence Cooley''' (born May 1, 1947) is an American politician and [[prosecutor]]. He was the [[Los Angeles County District Attorney]] from 2000 to 2012. Cooley was re-elected in 2004 and again in 2008.\n\nIn 2010, Cooley won the Republican nomination for California Attorney General against [[John C. Eastman]] and [[Tom Harman]] in the [[California state elections, June 2010|June 8 primary election]]. During the general election campaign, Cooley said he would defend [[California Proposition 8 (2008)|Proposition 8]], a 2008 ballot measure that banned same-sex marriages in California but was then being appealed in the federal courts. Cooley lost to the Democratic nominee, San Francisco District Attorney [[Kamala Harris]], in the [[California Attorney General election, 2010|November 2 general election]], a close race whose results were not finalized until November 24, 2010.<ref>{{cite web|title=Statement of Vote from the California Secretary of State|url=http://www.sos.ca.gov/elections/sov/2010-general/complete-sov.pdf|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140611025242/http://www.sos.ca.gov/elections/sov/2010-general/complete-sov.pdf|archive-date=2014-06-11|df=}}</ref>\n\n==Early life and education==\nThe second of five children, Cooley was born at [[St. Vincent Medical Center (Los Angeles)|St. Vincent's Hospital]] (now St. Vincent's Medical Center) in Los Angeles. His father was an [[Federal Bureau of Investigation|FBI]] agent and his mother a [[homemaker]]. Cooley attended Pater Noster High School in Los Angeles. At [[California State University, Los Angeles]], Cooley served two terms as student body president and was selected for membership in [[Phi Kappa Phi]]. He was also a member of [[Zeta Beta Tau]] [[Fraternities and sororities|fraternity]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Notable Alumni|url=http://www.zbt.org/who-we-are/notable-alumni.html|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161205230940/http://www.zbt.org/who-we-are/notable-alumni.html|archive-date=2016-12-05|df=}}</ref>\n\nIn 1970, he was commencement speaker for his graduating class. He entered the [[University of Southern California Law School]] and received his [[Juris Doctor]] in 1973.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://members.calbar.ca.gov/fal/Member/Detail/56789|title=Attorney Search : The State Bar of California|first=The State Bar of|last=California|date=|website=members.calbar.ca.gov}}</ref> That same year he joined the Los Angeles County District Attorney's Office. Cooley served over seven years as a reserve police officer with LAPD and 27 years as prosecutor. {{Citation needed|date=October 2012}}\n\n==Los Angeles County District Attorney==\nCooley challenged two-term incumbent District Attorney Gil Garcetti in the 2000 election. Garcetti and Cooley had a longstanding personal and professional rivalry, going back to at least 1996 when Cooley supported Garcetti's opponent for re-election, John Lynch. Garcetti defeated Lynch by a margin of approximately 5,000 votes out of slightly more than 2.2 million votes.<ref name=Cooley>{{cite web |url=http://articles.latimes.com/2000/nov/08/news/mn-48881 |title=Cooley Beats Garcetti by Wide Margin |work=The Los Angeles Times |author=Mitchell Landsberg and Twila Decker |date=November 8, 2000 |accessdate=December 1, 2018}}</ref> After the election, Garcetti demoted Cooley from a supervisory position to the county's obscure Welfare Fraud division. The move mirrored Garcetti's demotion as the chief deputy for the entire county in 1988 by then-incumbent [[Ira Reiner]], which caused Garcetti to challenge his former mentor and defeat him in the 1992 general election.<ref name=Ira>{{cite web |url=http://articles.latimes.com/1992-09-18/news/mn-676_1_chief-deputy/2 |title=Reiner, in Surprise Move, Drops Out of Race for D.A. |work=The Los Angeles Times |author=Sheryl Stolberg |date=September 18, 1992 |accessdate=December 1, 2018}}</ref>\n\nCooley upset Garcetti in a competitive three-person primary, taking 39 percent of the vote to Garcetti's 37, forcing the two into a runoff in the November general election.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://articles.latimes.com/2000/mar/09/local/me-7004 |title=D.A.'s Race Shapes Up as a Bitter Fight to the Finish |work=The Los Angeles Times |date=March 8, 2000 |accessdate=December 1, 2018}}</ref> In the two-person runoff, Cooley defeated Garcetti 64 to 36 percent.<ref name=Cooley/>\n\nHe was the first attorney with trial experience to be elected District Attorney since 1984. At his 2000 swearing-in ceremony, he charged his over 1,000 prosecutors \u2013 including more than 300 District Attorney investigators and 600 clerical, technical and support staff \u2013 to \"show no fear in pursuing the criminal element, but also be fearless in the pursuit of justice.\"\n\n===First term===\nCooley instituted a reorganization of the District Attorney's Office.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.losangelescriminallawyer.pro/media.html |title=Cooley Presentation to the Board of Supervisors |publisher=Citizens' Economy & Efficiency Commission |date=June 7, 2001 |accessdate=2014-11-20}}</ref> On April 9, 2003, he announced that he was closing the office's Environmental Crimes unit.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://articles.latimes.com/2003/apr/09/local/me-newhall9|work=LA Times|title=\"D.A. Shuts Down Environmental Crimes Division\"|via=Articles.latimes.com |date=2003-04-09|accessdate=2010-11-18 |first=Nicholas |last=Riccardi}}</ref> The closure left only one attorney to cover all environmental crimes in Los Angeles County. The reorganization also included the creation of the Justice System Integrity Division, Forensic Science Section and Victim Impact Program. Cooley changed the office's policy on California's [[Three Strikes Law]], with the stated purpose to assure proportionality in sentencing and even-handed application countywide. Throughout his time as District Attorney, Cooley continued his efforts against the Three Strikes Law in favor of proportionality, including supporting ballot measures that would have altered Three Strikes.  The blowback from those efforts ultimately led Cooley to leave the California District Attorneys Association in 2006.<ref>[http://www.metnews.com/articles/2010/cooley011410.htm \"Steve Cooley. County's Second-Longest Serving D.A. Takes Pride in Record, Looks to Future,\" MetNews, January 14, 2010].</ref>\n\nAs District Attorney, Cooley first made the headlines in the prosecution of [[Winona Ryder]] for shoplifting, the prosecution being based entirely on Cooley's political aspirations. Cooley filed four [[felony]] charges against her and led of team of eight prosecutors in what was described by British newspaper ''[[The Guardian]]'' as a \"[[show-trial]].\"<ref>{{cite news |url= http://arts.guardian.co.uk/fridayreview/story/0,,835207,00.html |title=Show trial |publisher=Guardian |date=November 8, 2002 | location=London | first=Duncan | last=Campbell}}</ref> Cooley was subsequently admonished by the California bar for his actions.\n\n===Second term===\nIn 2006, Cooley was the most notable law enforcement official to publicly oppose Proposition 83, better known as \"[[Jessica's Law]],\" a measure named after Jessica Lunsford, a 9-year-old who was raped and murdered by a paroled sex offender in Florida.  Cooley criticized Jessica's Law as being \"not carefully crafted,\" adding that \"Not liking sex offenders is a good thing and a popular thing, but when you are creating something to deal with them you have to think it through.\"<ref>{{cite web|last=Ainsworth|first=Bill|url=http://legacy.signonsandiego.com/uniontrib/20080222/news_1n22offender.html|title=Law creates homeless parolees, report says|work=San Diego Union Tribune|date=February 22, 2008 |via=Legacy.signonsandiego.com|accessdate=2010-11-18}}</ref> California voters passed Proposition 83 with 70.5% of the vote.\n\nDuring his second term, Cooley's office was unsuccessful in the prosecution of [[Robert Blake (actor)|Robert Blake]] for the murder of his wife [[Bonnie Lee Bakley]]. When interviewed about [[Robert Blake (actor)|Robert Blake's]] acquittal, Cooley publicly called members of the [[jury]] who acquitted Blake \"incredibly stupid\" and refused to apologize for the statement.<ref>{{cite news|author=Christine Lagorio|url=http://www.cbsnews.com/stories/2005/08/04/entertainment/main757429.shtml|title=\"No Apology For Robert Blake Jury\" CBS News|publisher=Cbsnews.com|date=2005-03-25|accessdate=2010-11-18}}</ref>\n\nAccording to the ''[[Los Angeles Times]]'', advocates for battered women criticized Cooley's handling of [[Deborah Peagler]]'s case and others like it.  In eight out of eight cases, he opposed the use of a California law that allows battered women in prison to be given a new hearing if evidence of domestic violence was omitted during the original proceedings. Cooley had initially supported Peagler's release from prison, but then withdrew his written offer to reduce the battered woman's prison sentence.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://pqasb.pqarchiver.com/latimes/access/1394400121.html?dids=1394400121:1394400121&FMT=ABS&FMTS=ABS:FT&type=current&date=Dec+7%2C+2007&author=John+Spano&pub=Los+Angeles+Times&edition=&startpage=B.5&desc=Lawsuit+says+Cooley+reneged+on+promise%3B+D.A.+vowed+to+aid+her+bid+for+freedom%2C+says+the+killer+of+a+pimp|work=The Los Angeles Times |title=\"Lawsuit says Cooley reneged on promise; D.A. vowed to aid her bid for freedom, says the killer of a pimp.\"|via=Pqasb.pqarchiver.com|date=2007-12-07|accessdate=2010-11-18|first=John |last=Spano}}</ref>\n\nJust a week before the 2008 election that he ultimately won, Cooley was attacked for violating Jessica's Law and making a deal with defense attorneys and judges to postpone seeking tougher sanctions against a group of serious sex offenders that had completed their prison terms. Rather than seeking indefinite hospitalization for some offenders, as allowed under a November 2006 ballot measure, Cooley only sought two years.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://articles.latimes.com/2008/may/31/local/me-cooley31|title=\"Sex offender deal an issue in campaign\"|publisher=Articles.latimes.com |date=2008-05-31|accessdate=2010-11-18|first=Jack|last=Leonard}}</ref>\n\n===Third term===\nIn June 2008, Cooley was elected to a third term, defeating his challengers, [http://www.SteveIpsen.com Steve Ipsen], President of the L.A. County Prosecutors Union, and Albert Robles, an attorney and professor. Cooley was heavily criticized for his opposition of Proposition 9 (Marsy's Law: The Victim's Bill of Rights). Cooley told the ''L.A. Times'', just before voters went to the polls over \"Marsy's Law\" that the measure, which ended up passing, would sweep aside \"decades of legislative scrutiny and judicial review.\" It plays to voters' feelings, selling itself with a female victim's name, \"like a cherry on the ice cream.\"<ref>{{cite news| url=http://articles.latimes.com/2012/jul/02/news/la-ol-cruise-ship-safety-law-all-wet-20120702 | work=Los Angeles Times | first=Patt | last=Morrison | title=Cruise ship crimes: Why so hush-hush? | date=2012-07-02}}</ref>\n\nThe ''L.A. Times'' editorial desk wrote on April 28, 2008 of Cooley, \"It is noteworthy that he criticized predecessor Gil Garcetti in 2000 for seeking a third term and promised that he would serve only two.\" But in 2008, he sought a third term, despite his promise.<ref name = \"Editorial\">{{cite news|author=LA Times Editorial Department|title=For District Attorney and Board of Supervisors The Times Reluctantly Endorses|publisher=Los Angeles Times|date=April 28, 2008|accessdate=2008-05-04|url= http://www.latimes.com/news/opinion/editorials/la-ed-endorsements28apr28,0,168282.story|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080529033326/http://www.latimes.com/news/opinion/editorials/la-ed-endorsements28apr28,0,168282.story|archivedate=2008-05-29}}</ref>\n\nOne of Cooley's 2008 re-election opponents, Albert Robles, faced misdemeanor charges filed against him by the D.A.'s office in November 2007. Robles was charged with printing a pair of political mailers without a return address and expending more than $100 cash in a political campaign. Robles accused Cooley of direct involvement in the charges brought against him because of a personal vendetta and to affect the outcome of the June 2008 D.A. election.<ref name=\"notguilty\">{{cite web|url=https://www.whittierdailynews.com/2008/10/22/jury-finds-water-board-member-albert-robles-not-guilty/|title=Jury finds water board member Albert Robles not guilty|publisher=Whittierdailynews.com|date=October 22, 2008|accessdate=2010-11-18}}</ref> Cooley denied those allegations.<ref name=\"notguilty\"/> In October 2008, a jury found Robles not guilty of all charges after deliberating for only 20 minutes,<ref name=\"notguilty\"/><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.whittierdailynews.com/2008/01/17/water-official-going-on-trial-over-campaign-fliers/|title=Water official going on trial over campaign fliers|publisher=Whittierdailynews.com|date=January 17, 2008|accessdate=2010-11-18}}</ref> and he was re-elected a month later to his seat on the board of the Water Replenishment District of Southern California.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.whittierdailynews.com/2008/11/05/robles-keeps-water-board-seat/|title=Robles keeps water board seat|publisher=Whittierdailynews.com|author=Mike Sprague|date= November 5, 2008 |accessdate=2010-11-18}}</ref>\n\nCooley was sued in federal court by the Association of Deputy District Attorneys. The suit was filed for allegedly violating the First Amendment of the United States Constitution.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.dailynews.com/2009/10/30/prosecutors-union-sues-la-county-district-attorney-steve-cooley/|title=Prosecutors' union sues L.A. County District Attorney Steve Cooley|date=October 30, 2009|publisher=|accessdate=February 2, 2018}}</ref> Judge Otis D. Wright II described District Attorney Cooley's actions as \"striking and rampant\". Judge Wright issued a preliminary injunction ordering Cooley to desist from behavior seen as discriminating and/or retaliating against employees on the basis of union membership.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.dailynews.com/2010/03/03/judge-orders-injunction-against-steve-cooley/|title=Judge orders injunction against Steve Cooley|date=March 3, 2010|publisher=|accessdate=February 2, 2018}}</ref>\n\nThe ''L.A. Times'' reported that \"Los Angeles County Dist. Atty. Steve Cooley waged an illegal anti-union campaign in which he and his staff harassed and unfairly disciplined union officers.\" Thomas S. Kerrigan, an L.A. County hearing officer for the Employee Relations Commission heard months of testimony and found that veteran deputy district attorneys and prosecutors under Cooley, with outstanding evaluations, were retaliated against. Kerrigan claimed that Cooley had conducted a \"deliberate and thinly disguised campaign\" aimed at destroying the union.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.latimes.com/news/local/la-me-cooley-union-20101112,0,4538052.story|work=Los Angeles Times|first=Jack|last=Leonard|date=2010-11-12|title=Cooley retaliated against prosecutors for their union work, hearing officer says}}</ref> The ''[[Metropolitan News-Enterprise]]'' reported that Kerrigan exchanged emails with an ERCOM executive showing biased ex-parte communications and the removal of emails from materials provided in discovery.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.metnews.com/articles/2012/expa042712.htm| work=[[Metropolitan News-Enterprise]]|first=Roger|last=Grace|date=2012-04-27|title=DA's Office: \"Improper Conduct\" led to ADDA Victory}}</ref> <!-- any further info?? -- this is two years old!! -->\n\nIn 2009, Cooley gained coverage all over the country when, along with federal authorities, he requested that the Swiss government arrest and extradite movie director [[Roman Polanski]], who was traveling to the Zurich Film Festival. Polanski had been a fugitive for 31 years after originally fleeing the United States in February 1978 after pleading guilty to unlawful sex with a minor in Los Angeles. Swiss courts dismissed the extradition request in July 2010 and released Polanski.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://articles.latimes.com/2010/jul/12/local/la-me-0713-polanski-freedom-20100712|title=Swiss refuse extradition, free Polanski|first1=Henry|last1=Chu|first2=Joe|last2=Mozingo|date=12 July 2010|publisher=|via=LA Times}}</ref>\n\nCooley, J.D. Fredricks (1903\u20131915) and [[Buron Fitts]] (1928-1940) are the only Los Angeles County district attorneys to serve three complete terms. Cooley did not run for a fourth term in 2012.\n\n===Policies===\n\nIn 2009, Cooley declared his opposition to medicinal marijuana dispensaries that sell over-the-counter in Los Angeles County.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://latimesblogs.latimes.com/lanow/2009/11/da-will-prosecute-dispensaries-even-if-la-does-not-ban-sales.html|title=D.A. will prosecute medical marijuana dispensaries even if L.A. does not ban sales|publisher=Latimesblogs.latimes.com|date=2009-11-17|accessdate=2010-11-18}}</ref>\n\nHis administration aggressively prosecuted political corruption in the City of Los Angeles as well as such communities as Bell, Vernon, Beverly Hills, Compton, Inglewood, South Gate, Temple, and Irwindale among many others. Cooley investigated state Senator [[Roderick Wright (politician)|Rod Wright]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.dailybreeze.com/news/ci_13388893?source=rss|title=State Sen. Rod Wright's district residency under investigation 09/21/2009|publisher=Daily Breeze|date=2010-03-09|access-date=2010-11-18|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120307175839/http://www.dailybreeze.com/news/ci_13388893?source=rss|archive-date=2012-03-07|df=}}</ref> for living outside of his elected district, and Inglewood Mayor [[Roosevelt F. Dorn]] for a low-interest loan from the City of Inglewood. Dorn and Wright were both convicted.<ref>[http://www.sfgate.com/cgi-bin/article.cgi?f=/n/a/2008/06/26/state/n225201D21.DTL San Francisco Chronicle: Inglewood Mayor Charged in Home Loan Scandal (6/26/2008)]   {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080702085200/http://www.sfgate.com/cgi-bin/article.cgi?f=%2Fn%2Fa%2F2008%2F06%2F26%2Fstate%2Fn225201D21.DTL |date=July 2, 2008 }}</ref><ref>{{cite news| url=http://www.latimes.com/local/la-me-rod-wright-verdict-20140129,0,5573020,full.story |newspaper=Los Angeles Times |first=Jean |last=Merl |title=State Sen. Roderick Wright found guilty of perjury, voter fraud |date=January 28, 2014}}</ref>\n\n==Career after public service==\nIn 2012, Cooley founded Steve Cooley & Associates, a consulting firm whose website states that it \"service(s) ... clients in the furtherance of their business ventures, advance(s) civil litigation, and advise(s) on criminal matters\". The distinction between civil and criminal litigation would seem to say that the company does not represent clients in criminal trials, despite the fact that Cooley's career has been in criminal prosecution.\n\n==Representation of David Daleiden and Center for Medical Progress==\n\nIn 2017, Cooley began to defend [[David Daleiden]], an anti-abortion activist and founder of the [[Center for Medical Progress]], after Daleiden and Sandra Merritt, were indicted on fifteen charges for surreptitiously recording several Planned Parenthood executives without their permission and claiming Planned Parenthood was illegally selling body parts from fetuses.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.latimes.com/local/lanow/la-me-ln-planned-parenthood-charges-activists-20170328-story.html|title=Two antiabortion activists behind undercover Planned Parenthood videos charged with 15 felonies|first=Matt|last=Hamilton|date= March 28, 2017|website=latimes.com}}</ref>\n\nAs part of the National Abortion Federation's lawsuit against Daleiden and the Center for Medical Progress, Federal Judge [[William Orrick III]] and the Ninth Circuit Court of Appeals issued an injunction forbidding Daleiden and CMP from publishing any more videos they had illegally obtained at private professional meetings.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/usa-plannedparenthood-video-lawsuit-idUSL1N10B1WX20150731|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170904120419/https://www.reuters.com/article/usa-plannedparenthood-video-lawsuit-idUSL1N10B1WX20150731|url-status=live|archive-date=September 4, 2017|title=Anti-abortion group is sued over video releases - Reuters|author=|date=July 31, 2015|website=reuters.com}}</ref> However, new videos then appeared on the website of Daleiden's attorney, former Los Angeles County District Attorney, Steve Cooley. Judge Orrick ordered Daleiden, and his attorneys, Cooley and Brentford J. Ferreira to appear at a June 14 hearing to consider contempt sanctions.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.latimes.com/local/lanow/la-me-ln-planned-parenthood-videos-20170525-story.html|title=Judge to consider contempt against antiabortion group leader after release of Planned Parenthood videos|first=Associated|last=Press|date=May 25, 2017 |website=latimes.com}}</ref> On July 11, 2017, Judge Orrick found attorneys Cooley and Ferreira in contempt of court saying, \"With respect to the criminal defense counsel, they do not get to decide whether they can violate the preliminary injunction\".<ref name=\"washingtonpost.com\">{{cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/national/judge-anti-abortion-leaders-attorneys-violated-court-order/2017/07/11/a7f095ce-669a-11e7-94ab-5b1f0ff459df_story.html|title=Judge: Anti-abortion leader's attorneys violated court order|author=|date=|publisher=The Washington Post|via=www.washingtonpost.com|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170712045537/https://www.washingtonpost.com/national/judge-anti-abortion-leaders-attorneys-violated-court-order/2017/07/11/a7f095ce-669a-11e7-94ab-5b1f0ff459df_story.html|archive-date=2017-07-12|df=}}</ref>\n\nOn July 17, Judge Orrick found Daleiden in contempt, as well as his lawyers and the Center for Medical Progress itself.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://m.sfgate.com/bayarea/article/Antiabortion-activist-lawyers-held-in-contempt-11295298.php|title=Antiabortion activist, lawyers held in contempt over secret videos|author=Bob Egelko|date= July 17, 2017|website=sfgate.com}}</ref> Judge Orrick ordered Mr. Daleiden to turn over video footage and other materials related to his 2016 preliminary injunction.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.washingtontimes.com/news/2017/jul/17/david-daleiden-contempt-court-posting-undercover-v/|title=David Daleiden in contempt of court for posting undercover videos online|first=Valerie|last=Richardson|date=July 17, 2017|website=washingtontimes.com}}</ref><ref name=\"washingtonpost.com\"/>\n\nOn August 31, Judge Orrick found Daleiden and his attorneys, Steve Cooley and Brentford Ferreira, liable for the payment of $195,359 to compensate the National Abortion Federation for legal fees and increased security for \"expenses incurred as a result of the violation of my Preliminary Injunction Order\". Judge Orrick wrote that Mr. Daleiden's attorneys, Cooley and Ferreira, were included in the sanctions intended to ensure \"current and future compliance\" with his order.<ref>[http://www.nationallawjournal.com/home/id=1202797026382 Federal Judge Sanctions Two California Lawyers in Abortion Videos Case], ''[[The National Law Journal]]'', Cheryl Miller, September 1, 2017. Retrieved September 4, 2017.</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.washingtontimes.com/news/2017/aug/31/david-daleiden-attorneys-fined-planned-parenthood-/|title=David Daleiden, attorneys fined $200,000 over undercover Planned Parenthood videos|first=Valerie|last=Richardson|date=August 31, 2017|website=www.washingtontimes.com}}</ref>\n\n==Family==\nCooley has been married to Jana, a former court reporter, since 1975. Their son, Michael, is a producer for [[Fox Sports]] and is married to a deputy district attorney. Their daughter, Shannon, is a deputy district attorney in the Los Angeles County District Attorney's office.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.metnews.com/articles/2010/cooley011410.htm|title=Steve Cooley. County's Second-Longest Serving D.A. Takes Pride in Record, Looks to Future|author=Kenneth Ofgang|date=January 14, 2010|website=www.metnews.com}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://losangeles.cbslocal.com/2015/09/09/woman-convicted-of-fatally-beating-elderly-man-at-metro-station/|title=Woman Convicted Of Fatally Beating Elderly Man At Metro Station|author=|date=9 September 2015|website=cbslocal.com}}</ref>\n\n==Election history==\n{{Election box begin no party no change |title=Los Angeles County District Attorney primary election, 2000<ref>{{cite web |url=http://apps1.lavote.net/General/ARCHIVES/OFFICIAL_ELECTION_RETURNS/PDFS/OER-58-