{"title_page": "Mortal Kombat X", "text_new": "{{redirect|MK X|other uses|MKX (disambiguation)}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=March 2017}}\n{{Infobox video game\n| title      = Mortal Kombat X\n| image      = Mortal Kombat X Cover Art.png\n| caption    = Cover artwork\n| developer  = [[NetherRealm Studios]]{{efn|Windows version developed by [[High Voltage Software]], later replaced by QLOC.}}\n| publisher  = [[Warner Bros. Interactive Entertainment]]\n| director   = [[Ed Boon]]\n| producer   = {{Unbulleted list|Hans P. Lo|Adam Urbano}}\n| designer   = {{Unbulleted list|Paulo Garcia|John Edwards}}\n| programmer = Gavin Freyberg\n| artist     = Steve Beran\n| writer     = {{Unbulleted list|Brian Chard|Dominic Cianciolo|[[John Vogel]]|Jon Greenberg}}\n| composer   = [[Dynamedion]]{{efn|Lead composer is Tilman Sillescu. Audio directors are Richard Carle and [[Dan Forden]].<ref name=\"Mortal Kombat X\">{{cite video game |title=Mortal Kombat X |developer=NetherRealm Studios |publisher=Warner Bros. Interactive Entertainment |date= |platform= |scene=Ending credits |level= |language= |quote= }}</ref>}}\n| series     = ''[[Mortal Kombat]]''\n| engine     = {{Unbulleted list|[[Unreal Engine 3]]<ref name=u3>{{cite web|last=Cavalli |first=Earnest |url=http://www.joystiq.com/2014/06/09/ed-boon-mortal-kombat-x-will-run-at-1080p-60fps/ |title=Ed Boon: Mortal Kombat X will run at 1080p, 60fps |publisher=Joystiq |date= |accessdate=June 27, 2014}}</ref>|[[Unreal Engine 4]] (mobile){{efn|Switched from Unreal Engine 3 to 4 with the version 2.0 update.<ref>{{cite web |title='Mortal Kombat Mobile' 2.0 Update Coming Next Week, Will Rework Old Characters |url=https://www.newsweek.com/mortal-kombat-11-mobile-20-update-1339992 |website=newsweek.com |accessdate=15 March 2019}}</ref>}}}}\n| platforms  = {{Unbulleted list|[[iOS]]|[[Microsoft Windows]]|[[PlayStation 4]]|[[Xbox One]]|[[Android (operating system)|Android]]}}\n| released   = {{Unbulleted list|'''iOS'''|April 7, 2015<ref name=\"mkxios\">{{cite web|url=https://itunes.apple.com/app/id949701151?mt=8|title=MORTAL KOMBAT X on the App Store on iTunes - Apple|accessdate=April 7, 2015}}</ref>|'''Microsoft Windows'''|April 13, 2015|'''PlayStation 4''', '''Xbox One'''|April 14, 2015<ref name=\"release_date\">{{cite web|url=http://shoryuken.com/2014/06/02/netherrealm-studios-releases-mortal-kombat-x-announcement-trailer/ |title=NetherRealm Studios Officially Announces Mortal Kombat X, Scheduled for 2015 |publisher=Shoryuken |date= |accessdate=June 2, 2014}}</ref>|'''Android'''|May 4, 2015<ref name=\"mkxandroid\">{{cite web|url=https://play.google.com/store/apps/details?id=com.wb.goog.mkx&hl=en|title=MORTAL KOMBAT X - Android Apps on Google Play|accessdate=May 4, 2015}}</ref>}}\n| genre      = [[Fighting game|Fighting]]\n| modes      = [[Single-player]], [[multiplayer]]\n}}\n\n'''''Mortal Kombat X'''''{{efn|Pronounced as [[X|the letter X]], not 10.<ref name=gamespot>{{cite web|last1=Makuch|first1=Eddie|title=Ed Boon Explains How To Say Mortal Kombat X|url=http://www.gamespot.com/articles/ed-boon-explains-how-to-say-mortal-kombat-x/1100-6420126/|website=gamespot.com|publisher=GameSpot|accessdate=September 12, 2015}}</ref>}} is a [[fighting game|fighting video game]] developed by [[NetherRealm Studios]] and published by [[Warner Bros. Interactive Entertainment]]. Running on the [[Unreal Engine 3]], it is the tenth main installment in the ''[[Mortal Kombat]]'' video game series and a sequel to the 2011 game ''[[Mortal Kombat (2011 video game)|Mortal Kombat]]''. It was released on April 14, 2015 for [[Microsoft Windows]], [[PlayStation 4]], and [[Xbox One]]. NetherRealm Studios' mobile team developed a version for [[iOS]] and [[Android (operating system)|Android]] devices. [[High Voltage Software]] developed the PC version of the game, with Polish studio QLOC taking over the work on it shortly after the release of Kombat Pack 1.\n\nLike previous ''Mortal Kombat'' games, ''Mortal Kombat X''{{'}}s gameplay consists of two players, or one player and the CPU, fighting against each other with their selected character, using a large, varied array of character-specific attacks. The game contains several modes, such as a story mode, which takes place twenty-five years after the previous ''[[Mortal Kombat (2011 game)|Mortal Kombat]]'' game, several 'Tower' modes, which feature dynamically changing challenges, numerous online modes, and the 'Krypt', a mode played in a [[First person (video games)|first person]] perspective, where players explore the areas unlocking a variety of in-game items.\n\nThe console versions of ''Mortal Kombat X'' received critical acclaim upon release. Most praise was directed at the game's controls, overall gameplay, graphics, story, and characters, with some reviewers calling it the best game in the ''Mortal Kombat'' series. However, the PC version of the game was met with mixed reception, with reviewers citing numerous technical issues (including frequent crashes and slow netcode) as problems that severely hinder the experience. Selling more than 10 million copies, the game was the fastest-selling game in the franchise and the ninth best-selling game in 2015.<ref>{{cite web |title=Mortal Kombat X has sold nearly 11 million copies |url=https://www.videogamer.com/news/mortal-kombat-x-has-sold-nearly-11-million-copies |website=VideoGamer.com |accessdate=12 April 2019 |language=en}}</ref>\n\nAn upgraded version of ''Mortal Kombat X'', titled '''''Mortal Kombat XL'''''{{efn|Pronounced as the letters XL, not 40.}}, was released on March 1, 2016, for PlayStation 4 and Xbox One, including all downloadable content characters from the two released Kombat Packs, almost all bonus alternate costumes available at the time of release, improved gameplay, and improved netcode. This edition was also released for PC on October 4, 2016, and was added to the [[Xbox Game Pass]] on December 7, 2018. A sequel, ''[[Mortal Kombat 11]]'', was released on April 23, 2019.\n\nIt is the best fighting game of all time.\n\n==Gameplay==\n{{See also|Mortal Kombat#Gameplay|l1=Gameplay of the Mortal Kombat series}}\n''Mortal Kombat X'' is a [[fighting game]] in which two characters fight against each other using a variety of attacks, including special moves, and the series' trademark gruesome finishing moves. The game allows two players to face each other (either locally or online), or a single player to play against the CPU. The energy meter, first introduced in [[Mortal Kombat (2011 video game)|''Mortal Kombat (2011)'']], allows players to perform techniques such as \"X-Ray\" special moves. Similarly to [[NetherRealm Studios]]' previous title, ''[[Injustice: Gods Among Us]]'', fighters are able to interact with the environment, using parts of the scenery to reposition themselves or using available objects as weapons.<ref name=sn>{{cite web|author= |url=http://www.shacknews.com/article/86189/mortal-kombat-x-producer-discusses-environmental-attacks |title=Mortal Kombat X producer discusses environmental attacks |publisher=Shacknews.com |date=September 8, 2014 |accessdate=April 6, 2015}}</ref> In addition, each fighter has three different variations, each featuring a different set of moves they can use during the fight: for example, the character [[Scorpion (Mortal Kombat)|Scorpion]] features a [[Ninjutsu]] variation which gives him specific moves utilizing dual swords, a Hellfire variation which incorporates fiery special moves, and an Inferno variation which allows him to summon hellspawn minions to aid him in the fight.<ref name=gb>{{cite web|url=http://www.giantbomb.com/videos/e3-2014-ed-boon-talks-mortal-kombat-x/2300-9076/?comment_page=2 |title=E3 2014: Ed Boon Talks Mortal Kombat X |publisher=Giant Bomb |date=June 11, 2014 |accessdate=June 22, 2014}}</ref>\n\nReturning from [[Mortal Kombat (2011 video game)|the previous ''Mortal Kombat'' game]] is the Energy Meter, which is divided in three sections, and provides access to enhanced special moves (costing one section), breaking combos (costing two sections) and performing X-ray moves (costing all three sections of the bar).<ref name=\":0\">{{cite web|url=http://kotaku.com/the-battle-for-earthrealm-continues-in-mortal-kombat-x-1584706283 |title=<nowiki>The Battle For Earthrealm Continues In Mortal Kombat X [Update</nowiki>&#93; |publisher=Kotaku.com |date= |accessdate=June 3, 2014}}</ref> Additionally, a Stamina Meter has been added under the health bar, which consists of two sections, and is consumed whenever the player runs, performs a back dash, a combo breaker, a stage interaction, or certain special techniques, such as cancelling Scorpion's teleports.{{citation needed|date=November 2016}}\n\n{{anchor|Quitality}}\nIn addition to the usual [[Fatality (Mortal Kombat)|Fatalities]], ''Mortal Kombat X'' features two new types of finishing moves: Quitality, which instantly kills the player's character if they [[rage quit]] during a multiplayer match;<ref>{{cite web|last1=Moser|first1=Cassidee|title=Mortal Kombat X Will Punish You For Rage Quitting|url=http://www.ign.com/articles/2015/03/19/mortal-kombat-x-will-punish-you-for-rage-quitting|website=IGN.com|accessdate=March 19, 2015}}</ref> and {{anchor|faction}}Faction Kills, a set of finishing moves available to players based on the selection of one of the game's five factions (Black Dragon, Brotherhood of Shadow, Lin Kuei, Special Forces, and White Lotus). [[Fatality (Mortal Kombat)#Brutality|Brutality]] finishing moves make a comeback, although different from the ones featured in ''[[Ultimate Mortal Kombat 3]]''. Brutalities now take the form of enhanced versions of certain moves that are triggered when said move is used as the final blow to win the final round in a fight, provided certain conditions are met.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://gamerant.com/mortal-kombat-x-brutality-jade-roster/|title='Mortal Kombat X' Devs Talk Brutalities, Which Fighter Won't Return|author=Anthony Taormina|date=February 12, 2015|work=Game Rant|accessdate=February 19, 2015}}</ref> In addition, the game features stage Brutalities, which are triggered when certain environment interactions are used to finish the opponent. Additionally, [[Fatality (Mortal Kombat)#Stage Fatality|stage Fatalities]] were reinstated in ''Mortal Kombat XL'', being available in three of the game's stages.{{citation needed|date=November 2016}}\n\nFor local single-player, the game offers Story mode, a plot-driven mode with cutscenes between fights; and Living Towers, an evolved form of ''Mortal Kombat'''s Challenge Tower where the play conditions change. Also locally, player vs. player mode is available. Playing online, the play modes include 1 vs. 1 (ranked or random), King of the Hill, Survivor, and Test Your Luck. Another new mode is Faction Wars, where players choose one from the five factions to align with, and join a persistent online [[cross-platform]] competition with others, winning points for their faction, contributing in the conflict between them, ranking up personally, and earning special rewards such as faction-specific finishing moves (one of which is unlocked to the player if their faction wins at the end of any given week).<ref>{{cite web|url=http://uk.ign.com/articles/2015/02/06/everything-we-know-about-mortal-kombat-xs-new-modes|title=Everything We Know About Mortal Kombat X's New Modes|work=IGN|accessdate=February 19, 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://nichegamer.net/2015/02/mortal-kombat-x-video-details-the-newest-feature-of-the-series-factions/|title=Mortal Kombat X Video Details the Newest Feature of the Series, Factions - Niche Gamer|work=nichegamer.net|accessdate=February 19, 2015}}</ref>\n\n==Plot==\n{{further|Mortal Kombat (comics)#Mortal Kombat X: Blood Ties|l1=Expanded backstory from the tie-in comic series}}\n\nTwo years after [[Mortal Kombat (2011) | the defeat of Outworld's ruler]], [[Shao Kahn]], [[Shinnok]] attacks Earthrealm with his army of Netherrealm demons, as well as Earthrealm warriors who were killed during Kahn's invasion and are now resurrected as revenants under [[Quan Chi]]'s control. After fighting their fallen comrades, a strike team led by [[Johnny Cage]], [[Sonya Blade]], and [[Kenshi (Mortal Kombat)|Kenshi]] open a portal to Raiden's Sky Temple and head to the Jinsei Chamber, the source of Earthrealm's life force, where [[Raiden (Mortal Kombat)|Raiden]] and [[Fujin (Mortal Kombat)|Fujin]] are seen battling Shinnok and his Netherrealm forces. When Shinnok tries to kill Sonya, Johnny rushes to defend her, inadvertently awakening ancient superhuman powers within himself. Using his newfound powers, Johnny holds Shinnok at bay long enough for Raiden to steal Shinnok's amulet and imprison him inside it, but Quan Chi escapes. Johnny, Raiden, and Sonya track him to his lair in the Netherrealm and defeat him, successfully restoring [[Scorpion (Mortal Kombat)|Scorpion]], [[Sub-Zero (Mortal Kombat)|Sub-Zero]], and [[Jax (Mortal Kombat)|Jax]] to human form in the process, though Quan Chi escapes again. In the years that follow, Johnny and Sonya marry and have a daughter, [[Cassie Cage|Cassie]], though they later divorce. Scorpion, now using his original name, Hanzo Hasashi, rebuilds his Shirai Ryu clan while mentoring Kenshi's son [[Takeda Takahashi|Takeda]], and Sub-Zero becomes the new Grandmaster of the Lin Kuei after killing [[Sektor]]. Sub-Zero uses the data from Sektor's memory banks detailing Quan Chi's various manipulations of the Lin Kuei, including the truth about the deaths of Hasashi's wife and son, to help end his feud with Hasashi.\n\nTwenty years after Shinnok's defeat, Johnny assembles a new team of young fighters composed of Cassie, Takeda, Jax's daughter [[Jacqui Briggs|Jacqui]], and [[Kung Lao]]'s cousin [[Kung Jin]]. After undergoing a training exercise with Sub-Zero, they are deployed to Outworld to resolve a civil war between former empress [[Mileena]], who has obtained Shinnok's amulet from [[Kano (Mortal Kombat)|Kano]], and Outworld's current emperor [[Kotal Kahn]], with whom Earthrealm has a fragile peace treaty. Meanwhile, in an Outworld refugee camp in Earthrealm, Sonya captures Kano and forces him to reveal Mileena's location. Using this information, Cassie's team aids Kotal in recovering Shinnok's amulet and capturing Mileena, who is subsequently executed on Kotal's orders. No longer believing Earthrealm capable of keeping the amulet safe, Kotal decides to keep it in Outworld's hands, and takes Cassie and her friends hostage as leverage against Raiden. Kotal's insectoid second-in-command [[D'Vorah (Mortal Kombat)|D'Vorah]], who had killed [[Baraka (Mortal Kombat)|Baraka]] when Kotal started his rule, is revealed as a double agent for Quan Chi and steals the amulet. Cassie and her team escape captivity, and inform Earthrealm of D'Vorah's intentions.\n\nHoping to stop Quan Chi from getting the amulet, Jax and Kenshi, aided by a Netherrealm local named [[Sareena]], lead an assault on the Netherrealm. After fighting his way through the revenants of his former allies, Jax captures a weakened Quan Chi, who is brought to Earthrealm and held at an Outworld refugee camp. Hasashi infiltrates the refugee camp alongside his clan with the intent of assassinating Quan Chi as revenge for ruining his life, defeating Kenshi, Johnny and Sonya in the process. As Hasashi prepares to kill Quan Chi, D'Vorah arrives with the amulet. Quan Chi manages to finish his spell moments before being beheaded by Hasashi, releasing Shinnok from captivity. Weakened by the Shirai Ryu's previous attack, Johnny is taken hostage by Shinnok and D'Vorah. With the aid of Quan Chi's revenants, Shinnok and D'Vorah assault the Sky Temple, and subdue Raiden and [[Bo' Rai Cho]] in the process. Shinnok then enters the Jinsei and corrupts it, transforming himself into a powerful demon in the process.\n\nCassie's team pursues Shinnok, only to be intercepted by Kotal Kahn and his army. They inform him of Shinnok's return and Kotal decides to kill them, hoping to appease Shinnok and buy time to bolster Outworld's defenses, but Sub-Zero and his Lin Kuei warriors appear just in time to repel the Outworld forces. At the Sky Temple, Jacqui and Takeda occupy the revenants, while Cassie and Jin enter the Jinsei chamber. Cassie defeats D'Vorah, though Jin is knocked out, leaving her to face Shinnok alone. When Shinnok begins torturing Johnny, Cassie manifests powers similar to her father's, which she uses to defeat Shinnok. A grievously-wounded Raiden then purifies the Jinsei, stripping Shinnok of his powers and forcing the revenants to withdraw. Sonya and her soldiers arrive to take Shinnok and D'Vorah away, and the Cage family reunites.\n\nSome time later, the revenants of [[Liu Kang]] and [[Kitana]] are revealed to have assumed leadership of the Netherrealm. Raiden, now in possession of Shinnok's amulet and corrupted in the process of purifying the Jinsei, warns them they will face [[Mortal Kombat 11 | \"fates worse than death\"]] if they threaten Earthrealm. Before departing, Raiden leaves behind Shinnok's severed, yet still living head as a final warning.\n\n===Characters===\n{{main|List of Mortal Kombat characters}}\nThe game had 24 playable characters at launch, with 9 additional characters added via [[Downloadable content|DLC]]. The playable characters in '''bold''' are new to the series, while the ones in ''italics'' are guest characters.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.gamesradar.com/mortal-kombat-x-roster/|title=Mortal Kombat X gets the Xenomorph, Leatherface, and a few old favourites|work=[[GamesRadar]]|date=December 4, 2015|accessdate=January 18, 2018}}</ref> [[Goro (Mortal Kombat)|Goro]] was available either as a pre-order bonus, or with the purchase of Kombat Pack 2.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://mortalkombatgamessupport.wbgames.com/hc/en-us/articles/360001114907-What-is-included-in-the-Kombat-Packs-}}</ref>\n\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\" \n! colspan=\"4\" |Base Roster\n! Kombat Pack 1\n! Kombat Pack 2\n|-\n|\n* '''[[Cassie Cage]]'''\n* '''[[List of Mortal Kombat characters#D'Vorah|D'Vorah]]'''\n* [[Ermac]]\n* '''[[List of Mortal Kombat characters#Erron Black|Erron Black]]'''\n* '''[[List of Mortal Kombat characters#Ferra / Torr|Ferra/Torr]]'''\n* '''[[List of Mortal Kombat characters#Jacqui Briggs|Jacqui Briggs]]'''\n|\n* [[Jax (Mortal Kombat)|Jax]]\n* [[Johnny Cage]]\n* [[Kano (Mortal Kombat)|Kano]]\n* [[Kenshi (Mortal Kombat)|Kenshi]]\n* [[Kitana]]\n* '''[[List of Mortal Kombat characters#Kotal Kahn|Kotal Kahn]]'''\n|\n* '''[[List of Mortal Kombat characters#Kung Jin|Kung Jin]]'''\n* [[Kung Lao]]\n* [[Liu Kang]]\n* [[Mileena]]\n* [[Quan Chi]]\n* [[Raiden (Mortal Kombat)|Raiden]]\n|\n* [[Reptile (Mortal Kombat)|Reptile]]\n* [[Scorpion (Mortal Kombat)|Scorpion]]\n* [[Shinnok]]\n* [[Sonya Blade]]\n* [[Sub-Zero (Mortal Kombat)|Sub-Zero]]\n* '''[[List of Mortal Kombat characters#Takeda Takahashi|Takeda]]'''\n|\n* ''[[Jason Voorhees]]''\n* ''[[Predator (fictional species)|Predator]]''\n* [[List of Mortal Kombat characters#Tanya|Tanya]]\n* '''[[List of Mortal Kombat characters#Tremor|Tremor]]'''<!--Do not remove the bolding; this is Tremor's first official appearance as a playable character.-->\n|\n* ''[[Alien (creature in Alien franchise)|Alien]]''\n* [[List of Mortal Kombat characters#Bo' Rai Cho|Bo' Rai Cho]]\n* [[Goro (Mortal Kombat)|Goro]]{{efn|Also available as preorder bonus.|group=note}}\n* ''[[Leatherface]]''\n* '''[[List of Mortal Kombat characters#Triborg|Triborg]]'''\n|}\n{{reflist|group=note}}\n\nAlong with series staples such as Scorpion, Sub-Zero, Liu Kang, Kitana and Raiden, several new fighters are added to the series' roster: D'Vorah, an insectoid humanoid who controls other insects; [[Ferra/Torr]], a symbiotic pairing consisting of a young armored female warrior and a giant masked brute; and Kotal Kahn, an [[Aztec]]-inspired \"blood god\" who is the new emperor of Outworld.<ref name=\"MKO1\">{{cite web |url=http://www.mortalkombatonline.com/content/News/read.cds?article=2096 |title=Introducing Kotal Kahn - Mortal Kombat X Loading Screen |publisher=Mortal Kombat Online |date=June 19, 2014 |accessdate=June 19, 2014}}</ref><ref name=\"MKO2\">{{cite web |url=http://www.mortalkombatonline.com/content/News/read.cds?article=2120 |title=NetherRealm Studios Creative Director Talks Through Official Raiden Trailer |publisher=Mortal Kombat Online |date=August 4, 2014 |accessdate=August 5, 2014}}</ref> With the game's story mode spanning 20 years, the game also introduces the offspring of several characters, such as Cassie Cage, the daughter of Johnny Cage and Sonya Blade; Takeda, son of Kenshi; and Jacqui Briggs, daughter of Jax. Other series newcomers include Kung Jin, an archer, cousin of Kung Lao; and [[Erron Black]], a [[Western (genre)|Western]]-style [[gunfighter]].<ref name=IDT>{{cite web |url=http://www.idigitaltimes.com/mortal-kombat-x-twitch-stream-reveals-mileena-and-takeda-fighting-variations-video-424259 |title=Mortal Kombat X Twitch Stream Reveals Mileena And Takeda Fighting Variations |first=Philip |last=Martinez |publisher=iDigitalTimes |date=March 19, 2015 }}{{Dead link|date=April 2020 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Cassie Cage, Kotal Kahn revealed for Mortal Kombat X, former character is daughter of Johnny Cage and Sonya Blade |url=http://www.eventhubs.com/news/2014/jun/10/cassie-cage-and-kotal-kahn-revealed-mortal-kombat-x-former-character-daughter-johnny-cage-and-sonya/ |website=EventHub |accessdate=June 11, 2014}}</ref> A non-playable demonic form of Shinnok called \"Corrupted Shinnok\" appears as the final boss. Also, [[List of Mortal Kombat characters|Tanya]] and [[Bo' Rai Cho]], who would later become downloadable characters, originally appeared in the story mode cutscenes, the former even being a non-playable opponent. Other notable characters that appear, but are not playable include [[Baraka (Mortal Kombat)|Baraka]], [[Sindel]], [[Rain (Mortal Kombat)|Rain]], [[Sareena]], and [[List of Mortal Kombat characters|Frost]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.polygon.com/2015/4/17/8441211/mortal-kombat-x-mod-baraka-rain-sindel|title=Mortal Kombat X modder's trick unleashes unplayable characters|first=Dave|last=Tach|work=[[Polygon (website)|Polygon]]|date=April 17, 2015|accessdate=January 18, 2019}}</ref>\n\nThe mobile game features five exclusive characters: Baraka, [[Jade (Mortal Kombat)|Jade]], Shao Kahn, [[List of Mortal Kombat characters|Kintaro]] and guest [[Freddy Krueger]].\n\n==Development==\nNetherRealm Studios began publicly hiring for the [[Eighth generation of video game consoles|eighth generation]] development in April 2012.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.gamespot.com/news/mortal-kombat-movie-producer-mentions-new-fighting-game-6412196 |title=Mortal Kombat movie producer mentions new fighting game |publisher=GameSpot.com |date=April 19, 2011 |accessdate=September 6, 2013}}</ref> In July 2013, it was confirmed that a new ''Mortal Kombat'' game was in development and was said to be released alongside the film series' reboot in September 2015.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://latimesblogs.latimes.com/entertainmentnewsbuzz/2011/09/mortal-kombat-movie-coming-as-warner-video-game-and-new-line-units-partner.html |title=New 'Mortal Kombat' movie coming via partnership of Warner units|publisher=Los Angeles Times |date=September 29, 2011 |accessdate=September 30, 2011}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last=Sheridan |first=Connor |url=http://www.gamesradar.com/new-mortal-kombat-game-works-producer-says/ |title=New Mortal Kombat game in the works, producer says |publisher=GamesRadar |date=July 30, 2013 |accessdate=September 6, 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://testyourmight.com/threads/next-mortal-kombat-confirmed-in-development-will-release-alongside-feature-film.36147/|title=Next Mortal Kombat \"confirmed\" in development; will release alongside feature film|publisher=TestYourMight.com|date=July 25, 2013|accessdate=September 17, 2013}}</ref> In February 2014, actor [[Kiefer Sutherland]] claimed he was participating in this \"huge game\" in an unidentified role.<ref>{{cite web | title=24 STAR KIEFER SUTHERLAND INVOLVED IN MORTAL KOMBAT GAME |url=http://ign.com/articles/2014/02/22/24-star-kiefer-sutherland-involved-in-mortal-kombat-game| publisher=IGN| accessdate=February 21, 2014}}</ref> The following June, Sutherland's involvement was denied by series creator [[Ed Boon]].<ref name=\"gamenguide\">{{cite web | url=http://www.gamenguide.com/articles/11636/20140617/mortal-kombat-x-news-boon-denies-kiefer-sutherland-involvement-promises.htm | title='Mortal Kombat X' News: Boon Denies Kiefer Sutherland Involvement, Promises 1080p & 60 FPS [VIDEO] | publisher=Game & Guide | date=June 17, 2014 | accessdate=November 17, 2014 | last=Caulfield | first=Luke}}</ref> According to the resume of [[Karen Strassman]], who voiced Kitana and Mileena in 2011's ''Mortal Kombat'', the game's working title was ''Mortal Kombat 2''.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://media.wix.com/ugd/cf1743_9fa434f7e42949508f4748c5074cd861.pdf|title=ANIMATION (Series & Features)|publisher=Media.wix.com|accessdate=January 17, 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.karenstrassman.com/karen_credits.pdf#!resume/c1ikp|title=Karen Strassman: Resume|publisher=KarenStrassman.com|accessdate=January 17, 2015}}</ref> The game's poster was leaked and an updated version of the series' iconic dragon logo was revealed on May 28, 2014. Boon posted daily riddles on his [[Twitter]] account that constituted a countdown suggesting a June 2 announcement date,<ref>{{cite web|last=Karmali |first=Luke |url=http://www.ign.com/articles/2014/05/06/mortal-kombat-creator-ed-boon-counting-down-to-something |title=Mortal Kombat Creator Ed Boon Counting Down To Something |publisher=Ign.com |date=May 6, 2014 |accessdate=June 4, 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.gameinformer.com/b/news/archive/2014/05/28/the-mortal-kombat-x-posters-are-real.aspx |title=[Update&#93; The Mortal Kombat X Posters Are Real, Ed Boon Updates Twitter Profile Pic - News |publisher=[[Game Informer]] |date= |accessdate=May 29, 2014}}</ref> hinting at the game's title being ''Mortal Kombat X''.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.polygon.com/2014/5/28/5758804/mortal-kombat-10-poster-rumor |title=Rumor: Mortal Kombat poster heralds franchise's return |publisher=Polygon |date= May 28, 2014|accessdate=May 29, 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last=Prell |first=Sam |url=http://www.joystiq.com/2014/06/01/mortal-kombat-x-listed-by-amazon-uk/ |title='Mortal Kombat X' listed by Amazon UK |publisher=Joystiq |date=May 29, 2014 |accessdate=June 3, 2014}}</ref> One of the Twitter clues left by Boon teasing this title was the image of a [[Lincoln MKX]] emblem posted with the comment, \"I wonder what the X stands for?\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://arcadesushi.com/mysterious-mortal-kombat-poster-suggest-franchises-return/ |title=Mysterious Mortal Kombat Poster Suggest Franchise's Return |publisher=Arcadesushi.com |accessdate=June 4, 2014}}</ref>\n\nOn June 2, 2014, the title was indeed officially revealed as ''Mortal Kombat X'', alongside an official reveal trailer featuring a fight between the iconic characters Scorpion and Sub-Zero.<ref>{{cite web|last=Karmali |first=Luke |url=http://uk.ign.com/articles/2014/06/02/mortal-kombat-x-officially-announced-with-trailer |title=Mortal Kombat X Officially Announced With Trailer - IGN |publisher=Uk.ign.com |date= |accessdate=June 2, 2014}}</ref> The game made its first public appearance at [[E3 2014]],<ref>{{cite web|last=Sliwinski |first=Alexander |url=http://www.joystiq.com/2014/06/02/mortal-kombat-x-announced/ |title=Mortal Kombat X announced (update: trailer, platforms) |publisher=Joystiq |date= |accessdate=June 2, 2014}}</ref> starting on June 10, 2014, where four new characters were revealed, apart from the two already revealed by the trailer.<ref name=\"dreadcentral\">{{cite web|url=http://www.dreadcentral.com/news/76540/e3-2014-mortal-kombat-x-new-screens-fighters-and-info#axzz34MsF8Wfj|title=E3 2014: Mortal Kombat X - New Screens, Fighters, and Info!|first=Steve|last=Barton|publisher=[[Dread Central]]|date=June 11, 2014|accessdate=June 11, 2014}}</ref> With over eleven million views, it was the third-highest viewed trailer on [[YouTube]] in the second quarter of 2014.<ref>{{cite web|last=Spangler |first=Todd |url=https://variety.com/2014/digital/news/call-of-duty-x-men-mortal-kombat-and-orange-is-the-new-black-top-youtube-trailer-views-in-q2-1201272179/ |title='Call of Duty,' 'X-Men,' 'Mortal Kombat' and 'Orange Is the New Black' Top YouTube Trailer Views in Q2 |publisher=Variety |date=June 30, 2014 |accessdate=July 31, 2014}}</ref> NetherRealm Studios said they are only working on the PlayStation 4 and Xbox One versions of the game.<ref name=gb/> The game, which runs at 1080p screen resolution and 60&nbsp;[[frame rate|FPS]],<ref name=u3/> has been said to feature the most brutal finishing moves in the series. Boon said: \"We have these meetings and everyone comes up with ideas for Fatalities. The ones that people say 'there's no way we can do that'\u2014they're the first ones we work on.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://blog.eu.playstation.com/2014/06/20/5-things-learned-mortal-kombat-x-e3-2014/ |title=5 things we learned about Mortal Kombat X at E3 2014 - PlayStation.Blog.Europe |publisher=Blog.eu.playstation.com |date= June 20, 2014|accessdate=June 27, 2014}}</ref>\n\nBy July 2015, due to heavy criticism for the porting issues that plagued the PC release of the game, almost all references to ''Mortal Kombat X'' had been removed from High Voltage Software's [[Facebook]] page.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Klepek|first1=Patrick|title=Sources: Warner Bros. Knew That Arkham Knight PC Was A Mess For Months|url=http://kotaku.com/sources-warner-bros-knew-that-arkham-knight-pc-was-a-1714915219|website=[[Kotaku]]|publisher=[[Gawker Media]]|accessdate=July 1, 2015|date=July 1, 2015}}</ref> It would later be revealed that work on the PC port had been handed over to Polish developers QLOC. On August 28, 2015, Warner Bros. announced the cancellation of the PlayStation 3 and Xbox 360 ports (originally scheduled for release at a later unspecified date) of ''Mortal Kombat X'' due to the inability to get the version for the last gen consoles to reach the quality standards set by the current generation.<ref>{{cite web|title=Mortal Kombat X PlayStation 3, Xbox 360 Versions Cancelled|url=http://www.ign.com/articles/2015/08/28/mortal-kombat-x-playstation-3-xbox-360-versions-cancelled|work=[[IGN]]|first=Cassidee|last=Moser|accessdate=August 28, 2015}}</ref> NetherRealm Studios community specialist Tyler Lansdown initially stated that Kombat Pack 2, ''Mortal Kombat XL'', and the enhanced online netcode would not be available on the PC version.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Walker|first1=Ian|title=Mortal Kombat X on PC Won't Receive Kombat Pack 2 Content|url=http://shoryuken.com/2016/01/20/mortal-kombat-x-on-pc-wont-receive-kombat-pack-2-content/|website=shoryuken.com|publisher=Shoryuken|accessdate=January 20, 2016}}</ref> However, on August 25, 2016 an open beta test period of the online functionality of ''XL'' was announced for the PC,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.pcgamer.com/mortal-kombat-xl-coming-to-pc-free-open-beta-this-weekend/|title=Mortal Kombat XL coming to PC, free open beta this weekend|publisher=PCGamer.com|date=August 26, 2016}}</ref> and ultimately a release date was set for October 4, 2016.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://shoryuken.com/2016/09/28/new-mortal-kombat-x-balance-patch-coming-on-october-4th-to-coincide-with-pc-release-of-mortal-kombat-xl/|title=New Mortal Kombat X Balance Patch Coming on October 4th to Coincide with PC Release of Mortal Kombat XL|publisher=Shoryuken.com|date=September 28, 2016}}</ref>\n\n==Release==\n''Mortal Kombat X'' was released worldwide (except Germany) for PC, PlayStation 4, and Xbox One on April 14, 2015. For reasons relating to the initial refusal by the German [[USK]] to issue the game with an age rating, the official German release of ''Mortal Kombat X'' was delayed until September 1, 2015. The game's ''Kollector's Edition'' includes a figurine of Scorpion and the Gold Scorpion skin, as well as future access to Kombat Pack 1.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://nichegamer.net/2015/02/kollectors-edition-for-mortal-kombat-x-revealed-comes-with-scorpion-statue/ |title=Kollector's Edition for Mortal Kombat X Revealed, Comes with Scorpion Statue - Niche Gamer |work=nichegamer.net |accessdate=February 19, 2015}}</ref> Simultaneously with the release of Kombat Pack 2 and ''Mortal Kombat XL'', the game received a free major update that introduced balance changes, one new stage (\"The Pit\"), several stage brutalities, and rollback-based [[netcode]] similar to [[GGPO]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.polygon.com/2016/1/15/10776282/mortal-kombat-x-network-code-ggpo|title=Mortal Kombat X is getting a networking code overhaul|publisher=Polygon}}</ref>\n\n===Downloadable content===\nBefore the game's launch, Goro was offered as a pre-order bonus. Later on, upon the game's release, he was also made available for purchase.<ref name=\"goro\">{{cite web |url=http://www.gamespot.com/articles/mortal-kombat-x-launching-april-2015-goro-fighter-/1100-6422129/ |title=Mortal Kombat X launching April 2015, Goro fighter revealed!|publisher=Gamespot.com|accessdate=January 17, 2015}}</ref>\n\nThe game has also received numerous [[downloadable content]] (DLC) packages, containing skin packs and occasionally new characters, such as the Ultimate Horror Pack, which includes Jason and horror-themed skins for Ermac, Reptile and Mileena; or the Predator/Prey Pack, which includes Predator and Predator-themed skins for Johnny Cage, Scorpion and a skin for Jax with the likeness and voice of actor [[Carl Weathers]] from the first ''[[Predator (film)|Predator]]'' film.\n\nOn March 13, 2015, [[Jason Voorhees]] from the ''[[Friday the 13th (franchise)|Friday the 13th]]'' franchise was announced as the first downloadable bonus character in the downloadable Kombat Pack season-pass bundle.<ref name=\"Mortal Kombat Online\">{{cite web|url=http://www.mortalkombatonline.com/content/News/read.cds?article=2318|title=Jason Voorhees Revealed For Mortal Kombat X Kombat Pass|publisher=Mortal Kombat Online|date=March 13, 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last=Karmali |first=Luke |url=http://www.ign.com/articles/2015/03/13/jason-voorhees-confirmed-for-mortal-kombat-x |title=Jason Voorhees Confirmed For Mortal Kombat X |publisher=IGN.com |date=March 13, 2015 |accessdate=April 6, 2015}}</ref> One week later, [[Predator (fictional species)|Predator]], from [[Predator (franchise)|the eponymous franchise]], was revealed as the second DLC guest character after he was inadvertently leaked by the [[Xbox Games Store]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ign.com/articles/2015/03/20/predator-dlc-character-outed-for-mortal-kombat-x|title=Predator DLC Character Outed for Mortal Kombat X|author=Michael Martin|work=[[IGN]]|date=March 19, 2015|accessdate=March 20, 2015}}</ref> with Tremor from ''[[Mortal Kombat: Special Forces]]'' and Tanya from ''[[Mortal Kombat 4]]'' later rounding out the cast of the Kombat Pack.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Chavez |first1=Steven |title=Tremor, Tanya, Predator, and Jason Voorhees are Mortal Kombat X's Kombat Pack characters, Liu Kang also confirmed |url=http://www.eventhubs.com/news/2015/mar/20/tremor-tanya-predator-and-jason-voorhees-are-mortal-kombat-xs-kombat-pack-characters/|website=eventhubs.com|publisher=Eventhubs|accessdate=March 20, 2015}}</ref> Ultimately, the pack was revealed to include all of the content in the Samurai Pack, Ultimate Horror Pack, Klassic Pack #1, Predator/Prey Pack and Klassic Pack #2.<ref>{{cite web |author= |url=http://community.wbgames.com/t5/Official-Announcements/What-you-get-with-the-Kombat-Pack/m-p/433947 |title=What you get with the Kombat Pack! - WB Games |publisher=Community.wbgames.com |date=March 27, 2015 |accessdate=April 6, 2015 |archive-url=http://archive.wikiwix.com/cache/20150408005951/http://community.wbgames.com/t5/Official-Announcements/What-you-get-with-the-Kombat-Pack/m-p/433947 |archive-date=April 8, 2015 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\nOn September 2, 2015, [[Ed Boon]] teased a Kombat Pack 2 DLC, which would include four new characters.<ref>{{cite web | author= |url=http://www.ign.com/articles/2015/09/03/new-mortal-kombat-x-dlc-announced-for-2016 |title= New Mortal Kombat X DLC Announced for 2016 |publisher=IGN.com | date=September 3, 2015| accessdate= }}</ref> On December 3, 2015, the characters for Kombat Pack 2 were revealed to be Bo' Rai Cho from ''[[Mortal Kombat: Deadly Alliance]]'', a new character named [[Triborg]] (a cyborg character that features [[Cyrax]], [[Sektor]], [[Smoke (Mortal Kombat)|Smoke]] and [[Sub-Zero (Mortal Kombat)|Cyber Sub-Zero]] as its variations), [[Leatherface]] from ''[[The Texas Chainsaw Massacre (franchise)|The Texas Chainsaw Massacre]]'' franchise, and the [[Alien (creature in Alien franchise)|Alien]] from [[Alien (franchise)|the eponymous franchise]]. Kombat Pack 2 also makes Goro playable for those who didn't have him as a pre-order bonus, and includes Kold War Scorpion, Kold War Pack, Apocalypse Pack and Klassic Fatalities #1 and #2. Kombat Pack 2 was ultimately announced for release on March 1, 2016 only on PlayStation 4 and Xbox One, marking the beginning of a period where the [[Microsoft Windows]] port was left aside for any updates and new DLC releases. Eventually it was released on PC on October 4, 2016 along with the PC release of ''Mortal Kombat XL''.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.eurogamer.net/articles/2016-10-05-it-looks-like-warner-has-fixed-mortal-kombat-x-on-pc|title=It looks like Warner has fixed Mortal Kombat X on PC|publisher=EuroGamer.net}}</ref>\n\n===''Mortal Kombat XL''===\nOn January 20, 2016, coinciding with the official announcement of Kombat Pack 2, NetherRealm Studios announced a new release of the game, called ''Mortal Kombat XL'' to be released simultaneously with said Kombat Pack, which would include all previously released downloadable content up to Kombat Pack 2. ''Mortal Kombat XL'' was then released for Xbox One and PlayStation 4 on March 1, 2016 in North America, and March 4, 2016 in Europe.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Kato|first1=Matthew|title=Mortal Kombat XL Includes Every Fighter, Skin & Fatality|url=http://www.gameinformer.com/b/news/archive/2016/01/20/mortal-kombat-xl-includes-every-fighter-skin-and-fatality.aspx|publisher=[[Game Informer]]|accessdate=January 20, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last1=Osborn|first1=Alex|title=Mortal Kombat XL Announced|url=http://www.ign.com/articles/2016/01/20/mortal-kombat-xl-announced?|website=IGN|accessdate=January 20, 2016}}</ref>\n\nWith the PC having been left behind after Kombat Pack 1, in August 2016 Ed Boon ran a poll on Twitter, which resulted in 45% of 10,000 voters saying they wanted ''Mortal Kombat XL'' for PC. After it ended, he posted the results, suggesting they would be acted upon.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://twitter.com/noobde/status/759575661535191040|title=Ed Boon Twitter poll|publisher=Ed Boon@Twitter}}</ref> Shortly after, an online-only beta was officially released on August 25, 2016 as a free-to-play title on [[Steam (service)|Steam]] in order to test the enhanced netcode, which lasted through September 1, 2016.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.polygon.com/2016/8/25/12646130/mortal-kombat-xl-kombat-pack-2-pc-release-steam|title=Mortal Kombat XL and Kombat Pack 2 now available on PC|first=Michael|last=McWhertor|work=[[Polygon (website)|Polygon]]|date=August 25, 2016|accessdate=August 26, 2016}}</ref> As soon as the beta ended, it was announced that ''Mortal Kombat XL'' (both as a full game for purchase, and as an update for ''Mortal Kombat X'' owners) would become available alongside the Kombat Pack 2 DLC on October 4, 2016, along with the updates that would bring the PC port back to parity with its console counterparts.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://testyourmight.com/threads/mkxl-enhanced-online-beta-feedback-kp2-coming-october-4th.61403/|title=MKXL ENHANCED ONLINE BETA FEEDBACK; KP2 COMING OCTOBER 4TH|publisher=TestYourMight| date=September 1, 2016| access-date=September 1, 2016}}</ref> As revealed by the game's updated intro credits, the porting of ''XL'' to the PC was handled by QLOC, in opposition to the previous problematic releases, by High Voltage Software. Coinciding with the release of XL for PC, an XL Pack was announced for existing owners of the game, which provides all of the previously existing DLC in a single package. Also coinciding with the release of the PC port of ''Mortal Kombat XL'' was a balance patch affecting most of the 33 characters in the roster in all three of the game's platforms.<ref>{{cite web|title=Patch Notes 10-4-16|url=http://community.wbgames.com/t5/Latest-Updates/Patch-Notes-10-4-16/ba-p/1297392|website=WB GAMES COMMUNITY|accessdate=October 4, 2016}}</ref>\n\n==Related media==\n\n===Mobile game===\nOn March 2, 2015, NetherRealm Studios announced that their mobile division would release an [[iOS]]/[[Android (operating system)|Android]] version of ''Mortal Kombat X'' in April 2015. The mobile game is described as a \"free-to-play fighting/card-battler hybrid\" and players would be able to unlock content in the console version of the game by playing the mobile version (and vice versa).<ref>{{cite web|title=A mobile version of Mortal Kombat X is also in development|url=http://www.warpzoned.com/2015/03/a-mobile-version-of-mortal-kombat-x-is-also-in-development/|website=Warp Zoned|date=March 2, 2015}}</ref> The iOS version was released worldwide on April 7, 2015, while the Android version was [[soft launch]]ed on April 21, 2015 in select Asian countries<ref name=\"androidasia\">{{cite web|url=http://news.softpedia.com/news/Mortal-Kombat-X-for-Android-Released-in-Google-Play-Store-But-It-s-Not-Available-to-All-479121.shtml|title=Mortal Kombat X Mobile released in select countries}}</ref> and was officially launched worldwide on May 4, 2015.<ref name=\"mkxandroid\"/>\n\nWith the 1.11 update version of the mobile game released on December 6, 2016, Freddy Krueger who appeared as a DLC character in ''[[Mortal Kombat (2011 video game)|MK9]]'' was added as a mobile-exclusive character using his signature moves and X-Ray attack from MK9.<ref name=\"mkxfreddy\">{{cite web|url=https://twitter.com/NetherRealm/status/806994436399960068|title=Freddy Krueger makes a splash on MKX Mobile}}</ref> On the update 1.13, Jade and Baraka were also added in the game as mobile exclusives, using their X-Rays from MK9. The latest version as of September 2017 (version 1.14) includes the popularly demanded Takeda, as well as the most recent addition to the ninja cast, Tremor.{{citation needed|date=September 2017}} By October 4, another update was released, featuring Goro (Klassic and Tigrar Fury) and Shao Kahn. A February 2018 update introduced Bo' Rai Cho and Kintaro. An October 2018 update introduced console DLC character [[Leatherface]]. In February 2019, the game was renamed ''Mortal Kombat Mobile'' with its 2.0 update with a vast overhaul of new features for ''[[Mortal Kombat 11]]''. Furthermore, the 2.0 update upgraded its graphics engine from [[Unreal Engine 3]] to [[Unreal Engine 4]].\n\nThe app has 50 million downloads on Android.<ref>https://play.google.com/store/apps/details?id=com.wb.goog.mkx</ref>\n\n===Promotions===\nPrior to the game's release, [[DC Comics]] published a comic book series based on the game, with the first issue released on January 6, 2015.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.comixology.com/Mortal-Kombat-X-2015-1/digital-comic/176368?ref=Y29taWMvdmlldy9kZXNrdG9wL3NsaWRlckxpc3Qvc2VyaWVz |title=Mortal Kombat X (2015-) #1 - Comics by comiXology |work=comixology.com |accessdate=February 19, 2015}}</ref> The debut trailer and opening cinematic features an original track by [[Wiz Khalifa]] titled \"Can't Be Stopped\".<ref>Jang, Esther. (June 3, 2014). [http://www.latinpost.com/articles/14123/20140603/wiz-khalifa-hot-new-song-2014-rapper-premieres-cant-be-stopped-in-mortal-kombat-x-trailer-watch.htm \"Wiz Khalifa Hot New Song 2014: Rapper Premieres 'Can't Be Stopped' in 'Mortal Kombat X' Trailer &#91;Watch&#93;\"] ''Latin Post''</ref> The official television commercial and launch trailer for the game were directed by [[System of a Down]] member [[Shavo Odadjian]] and featured the band's 2001 track \"[[Chop Suey!]]\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.gamespot.com/articles/mortal-kombat-x-uses-system-of-a-down-track-for-ne/1100-6426209/|title=Mortal Kombat X Uses System of a Down Track for New Live-Action Trailer|first=Eddie|last=Makuch|publisher=GameSpot.com|date=March 27, 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite av media|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=4faAvsMMpFg|title=Mortal Kombat X - Official Launch Trailer - PS4, PS3|date=April 6, 2015|work=YouTube}}</ref> The ''Mortal Kombat X'' logo was featured on [[NASCAR]] driver [[Erik Jones]]' #20 [[Xfinity Series]] car (sponsored by [[GameStop]]) that won the [[O'Reilly Auto Parts 300]] on April 10, 2015.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.sbnation.com/nascar/2015/4/11/8386683/nascar-texas-motor-speedway-2015-o-reilly-auto-parts-300-winner-erik-jones|title=18-year-old Erik Jones wins Xfinity Series race over Brad Keselowski, Dale Earnhardt Jr.| first=Jordan| last=Bianchi|publisher=SBNation.com|date=April 10, 2015|accessdate=April 12, 2015}}</ref> ''Mortal Kombat X'' has been used in [[eSports]] competitions, with international tournaments in Europe, Asia, and North America with $1,000 weekly tournament prizes starting on April 19, 2015 with a season final on July 11, 2015 worth at least $100,000.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://en.pro.eslgaming.com/mkx/proleague/|title=ESL MKX ProLeague - the first international tournament for Mortal Kombat X|accessdate=May 14, 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150402080900/http://en.pro.eslgaming.com/mkx/proleague/|archive-date=April 2, 2015|url-status=dead}}</ref> The ESL Pro League Season 1 Finals were won by Critical Reaction's Dominique \"Sonic Fox\" McLean using Kitana with Erron Black as a secondary. McLean earned a grand total of $60,000 from the Season 1 Finals.<ref>{{cite web|title=ESL MKX Pro League Season One Finals Overview|url=http://en.pro.eslgaming.com/mkx/proleague/news/esl-mkx-pro-league-season-one-finals-overview/|website=eslgaming.com|publisher=ESL Pro League Gaming|accessdate=July 27, 2015}}</ref> Season Two of the ESL Pro League for ''Mortal Kombat X'' began on October 18, 2015 and concluded in early 2016.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Tim Static|title=DETAILS ON THE ESL MORTAL KOMBAT X PRO LEAGUE SEASON 2; PRESEASON STARTS OCTOBER 18TH|url=http://testyourmight.com/threads/details-on-the-esl-mortal-kombat-x-pro-league-season-2-preseason-starts-october-18th.56563/|website=testyourmight.com|publisher=Test Your Might|accessdate=October 13, 2015}}</ref>\n\n==Reception==\n{{Video game reviews\n| MC = iOS: 66/100<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.metacritic.com/game/ios/mortal-kombat-x |title=Mortal Kombat X for iPhone/iPad Reviews |website=[[Metacritic]] |publisher=[[CBS Interactive]] |accessdate=July 11, 2018}}</ref><br />XONE: 86/100<ref name=\"MCXONE\">{{cite web |url=http://www.metacritic.com/game/xbox-one/mortal-kombat-x |title=Mortal Kombat X for Xbox One Reviews |website=[[Metacritic]] |publisher=[[CBS Interactive]] |accessdate=April 30, 2015}}</ref><br />PS4: 83/100<ref name=\"MCPS4\">{{cite web |url=http://www.metacritic.com/game/playstation-4/mortal-kombat-x |title=Mortal Kombat X for PlayStation 4 Reviews |website=[[Metacritic]] |publisher=[[CBS Interactive]] |accessdate=July 11, 2018}}</ref><br />PC: 76/100<ref name=\"MCPC\">{{cite web |url=http://www.metacritic.com/game/pc/mortal-kombat-x |title=Mortal Kombat X for PC Reviews |website=[[Metacritic]] |publisher=[[CBS Interactive]] |accessdate=April 30, 2015}}</ref><br />(''XL'') PS4: 85/100<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.metacritic.com/game/playstation-4/mortal-kombat-xl |title=Mortal Kombat XL for PlayStation 4 Reviews |website=[[Metacritic]] |publisher=[[CBS Interactive]] |accessdate=July 11, 2018}}</ref><br />(''XL'') PC: 84/100<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.metacritic.com/game/pc/mortal-kombat-xl |title=Mortal Kombat XL for PC Reviews |website=[[Metacritic]] |publisher=[[CBS Interactive]] |accessdate=July 11, 2018}}</ref>\n| Destruct = 8/10<ref name=\"Destructoid review\">{{cite web |last=Carter |first=Chris |date=April 14, 2015 |url=http://www.destructoid.com/review-mortal-kombat-x-290360.phtml |title=Review: Mortal Kombat X |publisher=[[Destructoid]] |accessdate=April 14, 2015}}</ref>\n| EGM = 7.5/10<ref>{{cite web |last=Carsillo |first=Ray |date=April 13, 2015 |url=http://www.egmnow.com/articles/reviews/mortal-kombat-x-review/ |title=Mortal Kombat X review |publisher=[[Electronic Gaming Monthly]] |accessdate=April 13, 2015 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150415233431/http://www.egmnow.com/articles/reviews/mortal-kombat-x-review/ |archive-date=April 15, 2015 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n| GI = 9.25/10<ref name=\"GI\">{{cite web |last=Shea |first=Brian |date=April 13, 2015 |url=http://www.gameinformer.com/games/mortal_kombat_x/b/playstation4/archive/2015/04/13/mortal-kombat-x-review-game-informer.aspx |title=A Deadly Alliance Of Old And New - Mortal Kombat X - PlayStation 4 |publisher=[[Game Informer]] |accessdate=April 13, 2015}}</ref>\n| GameRev = {{Rating|4|5}}<ref name=\"Game Revolution review\">{{cite web |last=Tan |first=Nick |date=April 13, 2015 |url=http://www.gamerevolution.com/review/mortal-kombat-x |title=Mortal Kombat X Review |publisher=[[Game Revolution]] |accessdate=April 13, 2015}}</ref>\n| GSpot = 8/10<ref name=\"GSpot\">{{cite web|last=Brown |first=Peter |date=April 17, 2015 |url=http://www.gamespot.com/reviews/mortal-kombat-x-review/1900-6416101/ |title=Mortal Kombat X Review |publisher=[[GameSpot]] |accessdate=April 17, 2015}}</ref>\n| GRadar = {{Rating|3.5|5}}<ref name=\"GRadar\">{{cite web |last=Sullivan |first=Lucas |date=April 13, 2015 |url=http://www.gamesradar.com/mortal-kombat-x-review/ |title=Mortal Kombat X review |publisher=[[GamesRadar]] |accessdate=April 13, 2015}}</ref>\n| GT = 8.4/10<ref name=\"GT\">{{cite web |last=Huber |first=Michael |date=April 15, 2015 |url=http://www.gametrailers.com/reviews/r5e3hy/mortal-kombat-x-review |title=Mortal Kombat X Review |publisher=[[GameTrailers]] |accessdate=April 15, 2015}}</ref>\n| GB = {{Rating|4|5}}<ref>{{cite web |last=Gerstmann |first=Jeff |date=April 13, 2015 |url=http://www.giantbomb.com/reviews/mortal-kombat-x-review/1900-703/ |title=Mortal Kombat X Review |publisher=[[Giant Bomb]] |accessdate=April 13, 2015}}</ref>\n| IGN = 8.4/10<ref name=\"IGN\">{{cite web |last=Ingenito |first=Vince |date=April 13, 2015 |url=http://www.ign.com/articles/2015/04/13/mortal-kombat-x-review |title=Mortal Kombat X Review |publisher=[[IGN]] |accessdate=April 13, 2015}}</ref>\n| PCGUS = 69/100<ref name=\"PCGUS\">{{cite web |last=Elliot |first=Matt |date=April 21, 2015 |url=http://www.pcgamer.com/mortal-kombat-x-review/ |title=Mortal Kombat X review |publisher=[[PC Gamer]] |accessdate=April 21, 2015}}</ref>\n| Poly = 8.5/10<ref name=\"Poly\">{{cite web |last=McWhertor |first=Michael |date=April 13, 2015 |url=http://www.polygon.com/2015/4/13/8364929/mortal-kombat-x-review-PS4-Xbox-One |title=Mortal Kombat X review: new blood |publisher=[[Polygon (website)|Polygon]] |accessdate=May 2, 2015}}</ref>\n| VG = 8/10<ref name=\"VideoGamer.com review\">{{cite web |last=Phipps |first=Brett |date=April 13, 2015 |url=http://www.videogamer.com/reviews/mortla_kombat_x_review.html |title=Mortal Kombat X Review |work=VideoGamer.com |accessdate=April 13, 2015}}</ref>\n| rev1 = ''[[VentureBeat]]''\n| rev1Score = 65/100<ref name=\"VentureBeat\">{{cite web|url=https://venturebeat.com/2015/04/16/mortal-kombat-x-i-love-you-but-i-hate-you-look-its-komplicated/|title=Mortal Kombat X, I love you...but I hate you. Look, it's komplicated|first=Stephen|last=Kleckner |publisher=VentureBeat|date=April 16, 2015|accessdate=April 16, 2015}}</ref>\n| rev2 = ''[[TouchArcade]]''\n| rev2Score = iOS: {{rating|4|5}}<ref>{{cite web |url=https://toucharcade.com/2015/04/08/mortal-kombat-x-review/ |title='Mortal Kombat X' Review \u2013 Vengeance Feels A Lot Like Justice |last=Musgrave |first=Shaun |date=April 8, 2015 |website=[[TouchArcade]] |accessdate=July 11, 2018}}</ref>\n| award1Pub = [[The Game Awards 2015]]\n| award1 = Best Fighting Game\n| award2Pub = [[Game Informer]]\n| award2 = Best Fighting Game<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.gameinformer.com/b/features/archive/2016/01/06/game-informer-best-of-2015-awards.aspx?PageIndex=4&PostPageIndex=2|title=Game Informer Best Of 2015 Awards|publisher=[[Game Informer]]}}</ref>\n| award3Pub = [[IGN]]\n| award3 = Best Fighting Game<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ign.com/wikis/best-of-2015/Best_Fighting_Game|title=IGN Best of 2015|publisher=IGN}}</ref>\n| award4Pub = [[Academy of Interactive Arts & Sciences]]\n| award4 = Fighting Game of the Year\n}}\n\n''Mortal Kombat X'' received mostly positive reviews. Aggregating review website [[Metacritic]] gave the Xbox One version 86/100 based on 21 reviews,<ref name=\"MCXONE\" /> the PlayStation 4 version 83/100 based on 81 reviews,<ref name=\"MCPS4\" /> and the Microsoft Windows version 76/100 based on 10 reviews.<ref name=\"MCPC\" /> It became the fastest selling game in the history of the ''Mortal Kombat'' series and topped the US<ref>{{cite web|url=http://gamerant.com/mortal-kombat-x-sales-ps4/|title='Mortal Kombat X' Tops PS4 Sales Charts|date=May 13, 2015|work=Game Rant|accessdate=October 7, 2015}}</ref> and UK<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.chart-track.co.uk/index.jsp?c=p%2Fsoftware%2Fuk%2Farchive%2Findex_test.jsp&ct=110032&arch=t&lyr=2015&year=2015&week=17|title=UK ARCHIVE SOFTWARE CHARTS|publisher=chart-track.co.uk}}</ref> PlayStation 4 sales charts in the month of release.\n\nBrian Shea of ''[[Game Informer]]'' called ''Mortal Kombat X'' \"more than the continuation of NetherRealm's successful vision for the franchise; it's one of the best fighting games in years\", adding that the core gameplay was complex and varied while he enjoyed the multiplayer options.<ref name=\"GI\" /> [[GameSpot]]'s Peter Brown enjoyed the overall gameplay, saying it had \"the best fighting mechanics of any game in the series\" but was critical of the downloadable content as \"there's so much to love about the new ''Mortal Kombat'' that it's a shame to see such blatant [[monetization]] practices overlap with your experience\".<ref name=\"GSpot\" /> Lucas Sullivan of [[GamesRadar]] described the story mode as \"ceaselessly entertaining\", having \"great voice-acting and a surprisingly enjoyable script\", and \"a pretty tough act to follow\", criticizing the other single-player modes outside of the main story, and \"sparse\" tutorial options.<ref name=\"GRadar\" />\n\n[[Destructoid]]'s Chris Carter scored the game an 8 out of 10 and called it \"one of the biggest fighting games of 2015\". Carter felt that as more characters are added via DLC, the game will get better over time.<ref name=\"Destructoid review\"/> ''VideoGamer.com''{{'s}} Brett Phipps gave the game an 8/10 and called it \"absurd, gruesome ridiculous fun\". Phipps mostly praised the story, character gameplay variety, and gore, but was annoyed by online \"hiccups\".<ref name=\"VideoGamer.com review\"/> Nick Tan from [[Game Revolution]] commended the gameplay, particularly complimenting the character variations, environmental attacks, Brutalities, the Krypt, and the Tower system. Tan also liked the overall presentation and the story's concept, but missed Stage Fatalities and tag-team matches, disliked the story's ending, and felt that the game was purposefully \"truncated\".<ref name=\"Game Revolution review\"/>\n\nMichael Huber of [[GameTrailers]] called it a \"superb entry in the franchise\", noting the gameplay, story mode and new online components.<ref name=\"GT\" /> Vince Ingenito of [[IGN]] gave it a score of 8.4. He claimed that ''Mortal Kombat X'' was the best ''Mortal Kombat'' game in the franchise's history, lauding it as deeper, mechanically richer and more fully featured than the previous ''Mortal Kombat'' games. He also praised the presence of the new characters as the major roster shakeup made the game feel new and exciting to longtime series fans and casual fans.<ref name=\"IGN\" /> Michael McWhertor of [[Polygon (website)|Polygon]] called the game \"one of the best fighting games in the series\", praising the gameplay in addition to the newer systems in place and overall presentation.<ref name=\"Poly\" /> Stephen Kleckner of [[VentureBeat]] was more critical of the game, citing in his opinion confusing move animations, a system favoring close range mid-to-high combos, having to use the block button to execute a run, poor online play, and easy Fatality DLC. He also mentioned an issue where save data would be erased due to a bug in the PC version.<ref name=\"VentureBeat\" /> Matt Elliott of [[PC Gamer]] had mixed feelings about the online gameplay and said that \"''Mortal Kombat'' online simply isn't sturdy enough to remain competitive\".<ref name=\"PCGUS\"/>\n\nIn October 2015, Warner Bros. confirmed that ''Mortal Kombat X'' had sold more than 5 million copies worldwide by then.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Hussain|first1=Tamoor|title=Batman: Arkham Knight, Mortal Kombat X Sell 5 Million Each Worldwide, Report Says|url=http://www.gamespot.com/articles/batman-arkham-knight-mortal-kombat-x-sell-5-millio/1100-6431342/|website=gamespot.com|publisher=GameSpot|accessdate=October 13, 2015}}</ref> It was the fastest-selling game in the franchise and was the ninth-best-selling retail game of 2015 in the United States.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.gamespot.com/articles/mortal-kombat-x-enjoys-biggest-launch-in-franchise/1100-6426680/|title=Mortal Kombat X Enjoys \"Biggest Launch\" in Franchise History|first=Eddie|last=Makuch|work=[[GameSpot]]|date=April 16, 2015|accessdate=March 14, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://venturebeat.com/2016/01/14/2015-npd-the-10-best-selling-games-of-the-year/|title=2015 NPD: The 10 best-selling games of the year|first=Jeff|last=Grubb|work=[[VentureBeat]]|date=January 14, 2016|accessdate=January 14, 2016}}</ref> The first-month sales of the game is higher than the first-month sales of every game released in April 2016.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.gameinformer.com/b/news/archive/2016/05/12/dark-souls-iii-leads-the-pack-during-a-slow-month-in-april-npd-report.aspx|title=Dark Souls III Leads The Pack During A Slow Month In April NPD Report|first=Ben|last=Reeves|publisher=[[Game Informer]]|date=May 12, 2016|accessdate=May 14, 2016}}</ref>\n\n===Awards===\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! colspan=\"4\" style=\"background:#B0C4DE;\" | List of awards and nominations\n|-\n! style=\"background:#ccc;\" | Award\n! style=\"background:#ccc;\" | Category\n! style=\"background:#ccc;\" | Result\n|-\n| [[The Game Awards 2015]]\n| Best Fighting Game\n| {{won}}<ref name=\"TGA: Nominees\">{{cite web | url = http://thegameawards.com/nominees/ | title = Nominees {{!}} The Game Awards 2015 | date = November 12, 2015 | website = [[The Game Awards]] | publisher = [[Ola Balola]] | accessdate = November 13, 2015 | url-status = dead | archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20151114024126/http://thegameawards.com/nominees/ | archivedate = November 14, 2015 | df = mdy-all }}</ref>\n|-\n| rowspan=2| 2015 [[National Academy of Video Game Trade Reviewers|NAVGTR Awards]]\n| Game, Franchise Fighting\n| {{won}}<ref name=\"navgtr\">{{cite web|title=NAVGTR Awards (2015)|url=http://navgtr.org/winners/2015-winners|website=National Academy of Video Game Trade Reviewers}}</ref>\n|-\n| Camera Direction in a Game Engine\n| {{nom}}<ref name=\"navgtr\" />\n|}\n\n==Sequel==\n{{main|Mortal Kombat 11}}\n\nA direct sequel to ''Mortal Kombat X'', ''[[Mortal Kombat 11]]'' was announced at [[The Game Awards 2018]]. It was once again developed by NetherRealm Studios and released worldwide on April 23, 2019 for [[Microsoft Windows]], [[Nintendo Switch]], [[PlayStation 4]], and [[Xbox One]].\n\n==Notes==\n{{notelist}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{Official website|https://www.mortalkombat.com/}}\n\n{{Wikiquote}}\n{{Mortal Kombat}}\n{{NetherRealm Studios}}\n\n[[Category:2015 video games]]\n[[Category:Android (operating system) games]]\n[[Category:Cancelled PlayStation 3 games]]\n[[Category:Cancelled Xbox 360 games]]\n[[Category:Crossover video games]]\n[[Category:Fighting games used at the Evolution Championship Series tournament]]\n[[Category:Interquel video games]]\n[[Category:IOS games]]\n[[Category:Martial arts video games]]\n[[Category:Mortal Kombat games]]\n[[Category:Multiplayer and single-player video games]]\n[[Category:NetherRealm Studios games]]\n[[Category:Ninja video games]]\n[[Category:PlayStation 4 games]]\n[[Category:Unreal Engine games]]\n[[Category:Versus fighting games]]\n[[Category:Video game sequels]]\n[[Category:Video games developed in the United States]]\n[[Category:Video games directed by Ed Boon]]\n[[Category:Video games featuring female protagonists]]\n[[Category:Video games with 2.5D graphics]]\n[[Category:Video games with downloadable content]]\n[[Category:Warner Bros. Interactive Entertainment games]]\n[[Category:Windows games]]\n[[Category:Xbox One games]]\n[[Category:Video games using Havok]]\n", "text_old": "{{redirect|MK X|other uses|MKX (disambiguation)}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=March 2017}}\n{{Infobox video game\n| title      = Mortal Kombat X\n| image      = Mortal Kombat X Cover Art.png\n| caption    = Cover artwork\n| developer  = [[NetherRealm Studios]]{{efn|Windows version developed by [[High Voltage Software]], later replaced by QLOC.}}\n| publisher  = [[Warner Bros. Interactive Entertainment]]\n| director   = [[Ed Boon]]\n| producer   = {{Unbulleted list|Hans P. Lo|Adam Urbano}}\n| designer   = {{Unbulleted list|Paulo Garcia|John Edwards}}\n| programmer = Gavin Freyberg\n| artist     = Steve Beran\n| writer     = {{Unbulleted list|Brian Chard|Dominic Cianciolo|[[John Vogel]]|Jon Greenberg}}\n| composer   = [[Dynamedion]]{{efn|Lead composer is Tilman Sillescu. Audio directors are Richard Carle and [[Dan Forden]].<ref name=\"Mortal Kombat X\">{{cite video game |title=Mortal Kombat X |developer=NetherRealm Studios |publisher=Warner Bros. Interactive Entertainment |date= |platform= |scene=Ending credits |level= |language= |quote= }}</ref>}}\n| series     = ''[[Mortal Kombat]]''\n| engine     = {{Unbulleted list|[[Unreal Engine 3]]<ref name=u3>{{cite web|last=Cavalli |first=Earnest |url=http://www.joystiq.com/2014/06/09/ed-boon-mortal-kombat-x-will-run-at-1080p-60fps/ |title=Ed Boon: Mortal Kombat X will run at 1080p, 60fps |publisher=Joystiq |date= |accessdate=June 27, 2014}}</ref>|[[Unreal Engine 4]] (mobile){{efn|Switched from Unreal Engine 3 to 4 with the version 2.0 update.<ref>{{cite web |title='Mortal Kombat Mobile' 2.0 Update Coming Next Week, Will Rework Old Characters |url=https://www.newsweek.com/mortal-kombat-11-mobile-20-update-1339992 |website=newsweek.com |accessdate=15 March 2019}}</ref>}}}}\n| platforms  = {{Unbulleted list|[[iOS]]|[[Microsoft Windows]]|[[PlayStation 4]]|[[Xbox One]]|[[Android (operating system)|Android]]}}\n| released   = {{Unbulleted list|'''iOS'''|April 7, 2015<ref name=\"mkxios\">{{cite web|url=https://itunes.apple.com/app/id949701151?mt=8|title=MORTAL KOMBAT X on the App Store on iTunes - Apple|accessdate=April 7, 2015}}</ref>|'''Microsoft Windows'''|April 13, 2015|'''PlayStation 4''', '''Xbox One'''|April 14, 2015<ref name=\"release_date\">{{cite web|url=http://shoryuken.com/2014/06/02/netherrealm-studios-releases-mortal-kombat-x-announcement-trailer/ |title=NetherRealm Studios Officially Announces Mortal Kombat X, Scheduled for 2015 |publisher=Shoryuken |date= |accessdate=June 2, 2014}}</ref>|'''Android'''|May 4, 2015<ref name=\"mkxandroid\">{{cite web|url=https://play.google.com/store/apps/details?id=com.wb.goog.mkx&hl=en|title=MORTAL KOMBAT X - Android Apps on Google Play|accessdate=May 4, 2015}}</ref>}}\n| genre      = [[Fighting game|Fighting]]\n| modes      = [[Single-player]], [[multiplayer]]\n}}\n\n'''''Mortal Kombat X'''''{{efn|Pronounced as [[X|the letter X]], not 10.<ref name=gamespot>{{cite web|last1=Makuch|first1=Eddie|title=Ed Boon Explains How To Say Mortal Kombat X|url=http://www.gamespot.com/articles/ed-boon-explains-how-to-say-mortal-kombat-x/1100-6420126/|website=gamespot.com|publisher=GameSpot|accessdate=September 12, 2015}}</ref>}} is a [[fighting game|fighting video game]] developed by [[NetherRealm Studios]] and published by [[Warner Bros. Interactive Entertainment]]. Running on the [[Unreal Engine 3]], it is the tenth main installment in the ''[[Mortal Kombat]]'' video game series and a sequel to the 2011 game ''[[Mortal Kombat (2011 video game)|Mortal Kombat]]''. It was released on April 14, 2015 for [[Microsoft Windows]], [[PlayStation 4]], and [[Xbox One]]. NetherRealm Studios' mobile team developed a version for [[iOS]] and [[Android (operating system)|Android]] devices. [[High Voltage Software]] developed the PC version of the game, with Polish studio QLOC taking over the work on it shortly after the release of Kombat Pack 1.\n\nLike previous ''Mortal Kombat'' games, ''Mortal Kombat X''{{'}}s gameplay consists of two players, or one player and the CPU, fighting against each other with their selected character, using a large, varied array of character-specific attacks. The game contains several modes, such as a story mode, which takes place twenty-five years after the previous ''[[Mortal Kombat (2011 game)|Mortal Kombat]]'' game, several 'Tower' modes, which feature dynamically changing challenges, numerous online modes, and the 'Krypt', a mode played in a [[First person (video games)|first person]] perspective, where players explore the areas unlocking a variety of in-game items.\n\nThe console versions of ''Mortal Kombat X'' received critical acclaim upon release. Most praise was directed at the game's controls, overall gameplay, graphics, story, and characters, with some reviewers calling it the best game in the ''Mortal Kombat'' series. However, the PC version of the game was met with mixed reception, with reviewers citing numerous technical issues (including frequent crashes and slow netcode) as problems that severely hinder the experience. Selling more than 10 million copies, the game was the fastest-selling game in the franchise and the ninth best-selling game in 2015.<ref>{{cite web |title=Mortal Kombat X has sold nearly 11 million copies |url=https://www.videogamer.com/news/mortal-kombat-x-has-sold-nearly-11-million-copies |website=VideoGamer.com |accessdate=12 April 2019 |language=en}}</ref>\n\nAn upgraded version of ''Mortal Kombat X'', titled '''''Mortal Kombat XL'''''{{efn|Pronounced as the letters XL, not 40.}}, was released on March 1, 2016, for PlayStation 4 and Xbox One, including all downloadable content characters from the two released Kombat Packs, almost all bonus alternate costumes available at the time of release, improved gameplay, and improved netcode. This edition was also released for PC on October 4, 2016, and was added to the [[Xbox Game Pass]] on December 7, 2018. A sequel, ''[[Mortal Kombat 11]]'', was released on April 23, 2019.\n\n==Gameplay==\n{{See also|Mortal Kombat#Gameplay|l1=Gameplay of the Mortal Kombat series}}\n''Mortal Kombat X'' is a [[fighting game]] in which two characters fight against each other using a variety of attacks, including special moves, and the series' trademark gruesome finishing moves. The game allows two players to face each other (either locally or online), or a single player to play against the CPU. The energy meter, first introduced in [[Mortal Kombat (2011 video game)|''Mortal Kombat (2011)'']], allows players to perform techniques such as \"X-Ray\" special moves. Similarly to [[NetherRealm Studios]]' previous title, ''[[Injustice: Gods Among Us]]'', fighters are able to interact with the environment, using parts of the scenery to reposition themselves or using available objects as weapons.<ref name=sn>{{cite web|author= |url=http://www.shacknews.com/article/86189/mortal-kombat-x-producer-discusses-environmental-attacks |title=Mortal Kombat X producer discusses environmental attacks |publisher=Shacknews.com |date=September 8, 2014 |accessdate=April 6, 2015}}</ref> In addition, each fighter has three different variations, each featuring a different set of moves they can use during the fight: for example, the character [[Scorpion (Mortal Kombat)|Scorpion]] features a [[Ninjutsu]] variation which gives him specific moves utilizing dual swords, a Hellfire variation which incorporates fiery special moves, and an Inferno variation which allows him to summon hellspawn minions to aid him in the fight.<ref name=gb>{{cite web|url=http://www.giantbomb.com/videos/e3-2014-ed-boon-talks-mortal-kombat-x/2300-9076/?comment_page=2 |title=E3 2014: Ed Boon Talks Mortal Kombat X |publisher=Giant Bomb |date=June 11, 2014 |accessdate=June 22, 2014}}</ref>\n\nReturning from [[Mortal Kombat (2011 video game)|the previous ''Mortal Kombat'' game]] is the Energy Meter, which is divided in three sections, and provides access to enhanced special moves (costing one section), breaking combos (costing two sections) and performing X-ray moves (costing all three sections of the bar).<ref name=\":0\">{{cite web|url=http://kotaku.com/the-battle-for-earthrealm-continues-in-mortal-kombat-x-1584706283 |title=<nowiki>The Battle For Earthrealm Continues In Mortal Kombat X [Update</nowiki>&#93; |publisher=Kotaku.com |date= |accessdate=June 3, 2014}}</ref> Additionally, a Stamina Meter has been added under the health bar, which consists of two sections, and is consumed whenever the player runs, performs a back dash, a combo breaker, a stage interaction, or certain special techniques, such as cancelling Scorpion's teleports.{{citation needed|date=November 2016}}\n\n{{anchor|Quitality}}\nIn addition to the usual [[Fatality (Mortal Kombat)|Fatalities]], ''Mortal Kombat X'' features two new types of finishing moves: Quitality, which instantly kills the player's character if they [[rage quit]] during a multiplayer match;<ref>{{cite web|last1=Moser|first1=Cassidee|title=Mortal Kombat X Will Punish You For Rage Quitting|url=http://www.ign.com/articles/2015/03/19/mortal-kombat-x-will-punish-you-for-rage-quitting|website=IGN.com|accessdate=March 19, 2015}}</ref> and {{anchor|faction}}Faction Kills, a set of finishing moves available to players based on the selection of one of the game's five factions (Black Dragon, Brotherhood of Shadow, Lin Kuei, Special Forces, and White Lotus). [[Fatality (Mortal Kombat)#Brutality|Brutality]] finishing moves make a comeback, although different from the ones featured in ''[[Ultimate Mortal Kombat 3]]''. Brutalities now take the form of enhanced versions of certain moves that are triggered when said move is used as the final blow to win the final round in a fight, provided certain conditions are met.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://gamerant.com/mortal-kombat-x-brutality-jade-roster/|title='Mortal Kombat X' Devs Talk Brutalities, Which Fighter Won't Return|author=Anthony Taormina|date=February 12, 2015|work=Game Rant|accessdate=February 19, 2015}}</ref> In addition, the game features stage Brutalities, which are triggered when certain environment interactions are used to finish the opponent. Additionally, [[Fatality (Mortal Kombat)#Stage Fatality|stage Fatalities]] were reinstated in ''Mortal Kombat XL'', being available in three of the game's stages.{{citation needed|date=November 2016}}\n\nFor local single-player, the game offers Story mode, a plot-driven mode with cutscenes between fights; and Living Towers, an evolved form of ''Mortal Kombat'''s Challenge Tower where the play conditions change. Also locally, player vs. player mode is available. Playing online, the play modes include 1 vs. 1 (ranked or random), King of the Hill, Survivor, and Test Your Luck. Another new mode is Faction Wars, where players choose one from the five factions to align with, and join a persistent online [[cross-platform]] competition with others, winning points for their faction, contributing in the conflict between them, ranking up personally, and earning special rewards such as faction-specific finishing moves (one of which is unlocked to the player if their faction wins at the end of any given week).<ref>{{cite web|url=http://uk.ign.com/articles/2015/02/06/everything-we-know-about-mortal-kombat-xs-new-modes|title=Everything We Know About Mortal Kombat X's New Modes|work=IGN|accessdate=February 19, 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://nichegamer.net/2015/02/mortal-kombat-x-video-details-the-newest-feature-of-the-series-factions/|title=Mortal Kombat X Video Details the Newest Feature of the Series, Factions - Niche Gamer|work=nichegamer.net|accessdate=February 19, 2015}}</ref>\n\n==Plot==\n{{further|Mortal Kombat (comics)#Mortal Kombat X: Blood Ties|l1=Expanded backstory from the tie-in comic series}}\n\nTwo years after [[Mortal Kombat (2011) | the defeat of Outworld's ruler]], [[Shao Kahn]], [[Shinnok]] attacks Earthrealm with his army of Netherrealm demons, as well as Earthrealm warriors who were killed during Kahn's invasion and are now resurrected as revenants under [[Quan Chi]]'s control. After fighting their fallen comrades, a strike team led by [[Johnny Cage]], [[Sonya Blade]], and [[Kenshi (Mortal Kombat)|Kenshi]] open a portal to Raiden's Sky Temple and head to the Jinsei Chamber, the source of Earthrealm's life force, where [[Raiden (Mortal Kombat)|Raiden]] and [[Fujin (Mortal Kombat)|Fujin]] are seen battling Shinnok and his Netherrealm forces. When Shinnok tries to kill Sonya, Johnny rushes to defend her, inadvertently awakening ancient superhuman powers within himself. Using his newfound powers, Johnny holds Shinnok at bay long enough for Raiden to steal Shinnok's amulet and imprison him inside it, but Quan Chi escapes. Johnny, Raiden, and Sonya track him to his lair in the Netherrealm and defeat him, successfully restoring [[Scorpion (Mortal Kombat)|Scorpion]], [[Sub-Zero (Mortal Kombat)|Sub-Zero]], and [[Jax (Mortal Kombat)|Jax]] to human form in the process, though Quan Chi escapes again. In the years that follow, Johnny and Sonya marry and have a daughter, [[Cassie Cage|Cassie]], though they later divorce. Scorpion, now using his original name, Hanzo Hasashi, rebuilds his Shirai Ryu clan while mentoring Kenshi's son [[Takeda Takahashi|Takeda]], and Sub-Zero becomes the new Grandmaster of the Lin Kuei after killing [[Sektor]]. Sub-Zero uses the data from Sektor's memory banks detailing Quan Chi's various manipulations of the Lin Kuei, including the truth about the deaths of Hasashi's wife and son, to help end his feud with Hasashi.\n\nTwenty years after Shinnok's defeat, Johnny assembles a new team of young fighters composed of Cassie, Takeda, Jax's daughter [[Jacqui Briggs|Jacqui]], and [[Kung Lao]]'s cousin [[Kung Jin]]. After undergoing a training exercise with Sub-Zero, they are deployed to Outworld to resolve a civil war between former empress [[Mileena]], who has obtained Shinnok's amulet from [[Kano (Mortal Kombat)|Kano]], and Outworld's current emperor [[Kotal Kahn]], with whom Earthrealm has a fragile peace treaty. Meanwhile, in an Outworld refugee camp in Earthrealm, Sonya captures Kano and forces him to reveal Mileena's location. Using this information, Cassie's team aids Kotal in recovering Shinnok's amulet and capturing Mileena, who is subsequently executed on Kotal's orders. No longer believing Earthrealm capable of keeping the amulet safe, Kotal decides to keep it in Outworld's hands, and takes Cassie and her friends hostage as leverage against Raiden. Kotal's insectoid second-in-command [[D'Vorah (Mortal Kombat)|D'Vorah]], who had killed [[Baraka (Mortal Kombat)|Baraka]] when Kotal started his rule, is revealed as a double agent for Quan Chi and steals the amulet. Cassie and her team escape captivity, and inform Earthrealm of D'Vorah's intentions.\n\nHoping to stop Quan Chi from getting the amulet, Jax and Kenshi, aided by a Netherrealm local named [[Sareena]], lead an assault on the Netherrealm. After fighting his way through the revenants of his former allies, Jax captures a weakened Quan Chi, who is brought to Earthrealm and held at an Outworld refugee camp. Hasashi infiltrates the refugee camp alongside his clan with the intent of assassinating Quan Chi as revenge for ruining his life, defeating Kenshi, Johnny and Sonya in the process. As Hasashi prepares to kill Quan Chi, D'Vorah arrives with the amulet. Quan Chi manages to finish his spell moments before being beheaded by Hasashi, releasing Shinnok from captivity. Weakened by the Shirai Ryu's previous attack, Johnny is taken hostage by Shinnok and D'Vorah. With the aid of Quan Chi's revenants, Shinnok and D'Vorah assault the Sky Temple, and subdue Raiden and [[Bo' Rai Cho]] in the process. Shinnok then enters the Jinsei and corrupts it, transforming himself into a powerful demon in the process.\n\nCassie's team pursues Shinnok, only to be intercepted by Kotal Kahn and his army. They inform him of Shinnok's return and Kotal decides to kill them, hoping to appease Shinnok and buy time to bolster Outworld's defenses, but Sub-Zero and his Lin Kuei warriors appear just in time to repel the Outworld forces. At the Sky Temple, Jacqui and Takeda occupy the revenants, while Cassie and Jin enter the Jinsei chamber. Cassie defeats D'Vorah, though Jin is knocked out, leaving her to face Shinnok alone. When Shinnok begins torturing Johnny, Cassie manifests powers similar to her father's, which she uses to defeat Shinnok. A grievously-wounded Raiden then purifies the Jinsei, stripping Shinnok of his powers and forcing the revenants to withdraw. Sonya and her soldiers arrive to take Shinnok and D'Vorah away, and the Cage family reunites.\n\nSome time later, the revenants of [[Liu Kang]] and [[Kitana]] are revealed to have assumed leadership of the Netherrealm. Raiden, now in possession of Shinnok's amulet and corrupted in the process of purifying the Jinsei, warns them they will face [[Mortal Kombat 11 | \"fates worse than death\"]] if they threaten Earthrealm. Before departing, Raiden leaves behind Shinnok's severed, yet still living head as a final warning.\n\n===Characters===\n{{main|List of Mortal Kombat characters}}\nThe game had 24 playable characters at launch, with 9 additional characters added via [[Downloadable content|DLC]]. The playable characters in '''bold''' are new to the series, while the ones in ''italics'' are guest characters.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.gamesradar.com/mortal-kombat-x-roster/|title=Mortal Kombat X gets the Xenomorph, Leatherface, and a few old favourites|work=[[GamesRadar]]|date=December 4, 2015|accessdate=January 18, 2018}}</ref> [[Goro (Mortal Kombat)|Goro]] was available either as a pre-order bonus, or with the purchase of Kombat Pack 2.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://mortalkombatgamessupport.wbgames.com/hc/en-us/articles/360001114907-What-is-included-in-the-Kombat-Packs-}}</ref>\n\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\" \n! colspan=\"4\" |Base Roster\n! Kombat Pack 1\n! Kombat Pack 2\n|-\n|\n* '''[[Cassie Cage]]'''\n* '''[[List of Mortal Kombat characters#D'Vorah|D'Vorah]]'''\n* [[Ermac]]\n* '''[[List of Mortal Kombat characters#Erron Black|Erron Black]]'''\n* '''[[List of Mortal Kombat characters#Ferra / Torr|Ferra/Torr]]'''\n* '''[[List of Mortal Kombat characters#Jacqui Briggs|Jacqui Briggs]]'''\n|\n* [[Jax (Mortal Kombat)|Jax]]\n* [[Johnny Cage]]\n* [[Kano (Mortal Kombat)|Kano]]\n* [[Kenshi (Mortal Kombat)|Kenshi]]\n* [[Kitana]]\n* '''[[List of Mortal Kombat characters#Kotal Kahn|Kotal Kahn]]'''\n|\n* '''[[List of Mortal Kombat characters#Kung Jin|Kung Jin]]'''\n* [[Kung Lao]]\n* [[Liu Kang]]\n* [[Mileena]]\n* [[Quan Chi]]\n* [[Raiden (Mortal Kombat)|Raiden]]\n|\n* [[Reptile (Mortal Kombat)|Reptile]]\n* [[Scorpion (Mortal Kombat)|Scorpion]]\n* [[Shinnok]]\n* [[Sonya Blade]]\n* [[Sub-Zero (Mortal Kombat)|Sub-Zero]]\n* '''[[List of Mortal Kombat characters#Takeda Takahashi|Takeda]]'''\n|\n* ''[[Jason Voorhees]]''\n* ''[[Predator (fictional species)|Predator]]''\n* [[List of Mortal Kombat characters#Tanya|Tanya]]\n* '''[[List of Mortal Kombat characters#Tremor|Tremor]]'''<!--Do not remove the bolding; this is Tremor's first official appearance as a playable character.-->\n|\n* ''[[Alien (creature in Alien franchise)|Alien]]''\n* [[List of Mortal Kombat characters#Bo' Rai Cho|Bo' Rai Cho]]\n* [[Goro (Mortal Kombat)|Goro]]{{efn|Also available as preorder bonus.|group=note}}\n* ''[[Leatherface]]''\n* '''[[List of Mortal Kombat characters#Triborg|Triborg]]'''\n|}\n{{reflist|group=note}}\n\nAlong with series staples such as Scorpion, Sub-Zero, Liu Kang, Kitana and Raiden, several new fighters are added to the series' roster: D'Vorah, an insectoid humanoid who controls other insects; [[Ferra/Torr]], a symbiotic pairing consisting of a young armored female warrior and a giant masked brute; and Kotal Kahn, an [[Aztec]]-inspired \"blood god\" who is the new emperor of Outworld.<ref name=\"MKO1\">{{cite web |url=http://www.mortalkombatonline.com/content/News/read.cds?article=2096 |title=Introducing Kotal Kahn - Mortal Kombat X Loading Screen |publisher=Mortal Kombat Online |date=June 19, 2014 |accessdate=June 19, 2014}}</ref><ref name=\"MKO2\">{{cite web |url=http://www.mortalkombatonline.com/content/News/read.cds?article=2120 |title=NetherRealm Studios Creative Director Talks Through Official Raiden Trailer |publisher=Mortal Kombat Online |date=August 4, 2014 |accessdate=August 5, 2014}}</ref> With the game's story mode spanning 20 years, the game also introduces the offspring of several characters, such as Cassie Cage, the daughter of Johnny Cage and Sonya Blade; Takeda, son of Kenshi; and Jacqui Briggs, daughter of Jax. Other series newcomers include Kung Jin, an archer, cousin of Kung Lao; and [[Erron Black]], a [[Western (genre)|Western]]-style [[gunfighter]].<ref name=IDT>{{cite web |url=http://www.idigitaltimes.com/mortal-kombat-x-twitch-stream-reveals-mileena-and-takeda-fighting-variations-video-424259 |title=Mortal Kombat X Twitch Stream Reveals Mileena And Takeda Fighting Variations |first=Philip |last=Martinez |publisher=iDigitalTimes |date=March 19, 2015 }}{{Dead link|date=April 2020 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Cassie Cage, Kotal Kahn revealed for Mortal Kombat X, former character is daughter of Johnny Cage and Sonya Blade |url=http://www.eventhubs.com/news/2014/jun/10/cassie-cage-and-kotal-kahn-revealed-mortal-kombat-x-former-character-daughter-johnny-cage-and-sonya/ |website=EventHub |accessdate=June 11, 2014}}</ref> A non-playable demonic form of Shinnok called \"Corrupted Shinnok\" appears as the final boss. Also, [[List of Mortal Kombat characters|Tanya]] and [[Bo' Rai Cho]], who would later become downloadable characters, originally appeared in the story mode cutscenes, the former even being a non-playable opponent. Other notable characters that appear, but are not playable include [[Baraka (Mortal Kombat)|Baraka]], [[Sindel]], [[Rain (Mortal Kombat)|Rain]], [[Sareena]], and [[List of Mortal Kombat characters|Frost]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.polygon.com/2015/4/17/8441211/mortal-kombat-x-mod-baraka-rain-sindel|title=Mortal Kombat X modder's trick unleashes unplayable characters|first=Dave|last=Tach|work=[[Polygon (website)|Polygon]]|date=April 17, 2015|accessdate=January 18, 2019}}</ref>\n\nThe mobile game features five exclusive characters: Baraka, [[Jade (Mortal Kombat)|Jade]], Shao Kahn, [[List of Mortal Kombat characters|Kintaro]] and guest [[Freddy Krueger]].\n\n==Development==\nNetherRealm Studios began publicly hiring for the [[Eighth generation of video game consoles|eighth generation]] development in April 2012.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.gamespot.com/news/mortal-kombat-movie-producer-mentions-new-fighting-game-6412196 |title=Mortal Kombat movie producer mentions new fighting game |publisher=GameSpot.com |date=April 19, 2011 |accessdate=September 6, 2013}}</ref> In July 2013, it was confirmed that a new ''Mortal Kombat'' game was in development and was said to be released alongside the film series' reboot in September 2015.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://latimesblogs.latimes.com/entertainmentnewsbuzz/2011/09/mortal-kombat-movie-coming-as-warner-video-game-and-new-line-units-partner.html |title=New 'Mortal Kombat' movie coming via partnership of Warner units|publisher=Los Angeles Times |date=September 29, 2011 |accessdate=September 30, 2011}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last=Sheridan |first=Connor |url=http://www.gamesradar.com/new-mortal-kombat-game-works-producer-says/ |title=New Mortal Kombat game in the works, producer says |publisher=GamesRadar |date=July 30, 2013 |accessdate=September 6, 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://testyourmight.com/threads/next-mortal-kombat-confirmed-in-development-will-release-alongside-feature-film.36147/|title=Next Mortal Kombat \"confirmed\" in development; will release alongside feature film|publisher=TestYourMight.com|date=July 25, 2013|accessdate=September 17, 2013}}</ref> In February 2014, actor [[Kiefer Sutherland]] claimed he was participating in this \"huge game\" in an unidentified role.<ref>{{cite web | title=24 STAR KIEFER SUTHERLAND INVOLVED IN MORTAL KOMBAT GAME |url=http://ign.com/articles/2014/02/22/24-star-kiefer-sutherland-involved-in-mortal-kombat-game| publisher=IGN| accessdate=February 21, 2014}}</ref> The following June, Sutherland's involvement was denied by series creator [[Ed Boon]].<ref name=\"gamenguide\">{{cite web | url=http://www.gamenguide.com/articles/11636/20140617/mortal-kombat-x-news-boon-denies-kiefer-sutherland-involvement-promises.htm | title='Mortal Kombat X' News: Boon Denies Kiefer Sutherland Involvement, Promises 1080p & 60 FPS [VIDEO] | publisher=Game & Guide | date=June 17, 2014 | accessdate=November 17, 2014 | last=Caulfield | first=Luke}}</ref> According to the resume of [[Karen Strassman]], who voiced Kitana and Mileena in 2011's ''Mortal Kombat'', the game's working title was ''Mortal Kombat 2''.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://media.wix.com/ugd/cf1743_9fa434f7e42949508f4748c5074cd861.pdf|title=ANIMATION (Series & Features)|publisher=Media.wix.com|accessdate=January 17, 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.karenstrassman.com/karen_credits.pdf#!resume/c1ikp|title=Karen Strassman: Resume|publisher=KarenStrassman.com|accessdate=January 17, 2015}}</ref> The game's poster was leaked and an updated version of the series' iconic dragon logo was revealed on May 28, 2014. Boon posted daily riddles on his [[Twitter]] account that constituted a countdown suggesting a June 2 announcement date,<ref>{{cite web|last=Karmali |first=Luke |url=http://www.ign.com/articles/2014/05/06/mortal-kombat-creator-ed-boon-counting-down-to-something |title=Mortal Kombat Creator Ed Boon Counting Down To Something |publisher=Ign.com |date=May 6, 2014 |accessdate=June 4, 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.gameinformer.com/b/news/archive/2014/05/28/the-mortal-kombat-x-posters-are-real.aspx |title=[Update&#93; The Mortal Kombat X Posters Are Real, Ed Boon Updates Twitter Profile Pic - News |publisher=[[Game Informer]] |date= |accessdate=May 29, 2014}}</ref> hinting at the game's title being ''Mortal Kombat X''.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.polygon.com/2014/5/28/5758804/mortal-kombat-10-poster-rumor |title=Rumor: Mortal Kombat poster heralds franchise's return |publisher=Polygon |date= May 28, 2014|accessdate=May 29, 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last=Prell |first=Sam |url=http://www.joystiq.com/2014/06/01/mortal-kombat-x-listed-by-amazon-uk/ |title='Mortal Kombat X' listed by Amazon UK |publisher=Joystiq |date=May 29, 2014 |accessdate=June 3, 2014}}</ref> One of the Twitter clues left by Boon teasing this title was the image of a [[Lincoln MKX]] emblem posted with the comment, \"I wonder what the X stands for?\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://arcadesushi.com/mysterious-mortal-kombat-poster-suggest-franchises-return/ |title=Mysterious Mortal Kombat Poster Suggest Franchise's Return |publisher=Arcadesushi.com |accessdate=June 4, 2014}}</ref>\n\nOn June 2, 2014, the title was indeed officially revealed as ''Mortal Kombat X'', alongside an official reveal trailer featuring a fight between the iconic characters Scorpion and Sub-Zero.<ref>{{cite web|last=Karmali |first=Luke |url=http://uk.ign.com/articles/2014/06/02/mortal-kombat-x-officially-announced-with-trailer |title=Mortal Kombat X Officially Announced With Trailer - IGN |publisher=Uk.ign.com |date= |accessdate=June 2, 2014}}</ref> The game made its first public appearance at [[E3 2014]],<ref>{{cite web|last=Sliwinski |first=Alexander |url=http://www.joystiq.com/2014/06/02/mortal-kombat-x-announced/ |title=Mortal Kombat X announced (update: trailer, platforms) |publisher=Joystiq |date= |accessdate=June 2, 2014}}</ref> starting on June 10, 2014, where four new characters were revealed, apart from the two already revealed by the trailer.<ref name=\"dreadcentral\">{{cite web|url=http://www.dreadcentral.com/news/76540/e3-2014-mortal-kombat-x-new-screens-fighters-and-info#axzz34MsF8Wfj|title=E3 2014: Mortal Kombat X - New Screens, Fighters, and Info!|first=Steve|last=Barton|publisher=[[Dread Central]]|date=June 11, 2014|accessdate=June 11, 2014}}</ref> With over eleven million views, it was the third-highest viewed trailer on [[YouTube]] in the second quarter of 2014.<ref>{{cite web|last=Spangler |first=Todd |url=https://variety.com/2014/digital/news/call-of-duty-x-men-mortal-kombat-and-orange-is-the-new-black-top-youtube-trailer-views-in-q2-1201272179/ |title='Call of Duty,' 'X-Men,' 'Mortal Kombat' and 'Orange Is the New Black' Top YouTube Trailer Views in Q2 |publisher=Variety |date=June 30, 2014 |accessdate=July 31, 2014}}</ref> NetherRealm Studios said they are only working on the PlayStation 4 and Xbox One versions of the game.<ref name=gb/> The game, which runs at 1080p screen resolution and 60&nbsp;[[frame rate|FPS]],<ref name=u3/> has been said to feature the most brutal finishing moves in the series. Boon said: \"We have these meetings and everyone comes up with ideas for Fatalities. The ones that people say 'there's no way we can do that'\u2014they're the first ones we work on.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://blog.eu.playstation.com/2014/06/20/5-things-learned-mortal-kombat-x-e3-2014/ |title=5 things we learned about Mortal Kombat X at E3 2014 - PlayStation.Blog.Europe |publisher=Blog.eu.playstation.com |date= June 20, 2014|accessdate=June 27, 2014}}</ref>\n\nBy July 2015, due to heavy criticism for the porting issues that plagued the PC release of the game, almost all references to ''Mortal Kombat X'' had been removed from High Voltage Software's [[Facebook]] page.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Klepek|first1=Patrick|title=Sources: Warner Bros. Knew That Arkham Knight PC Was A Mess For Months|url=http://kotaku.com/sources-warner-bros-knew-that-arkham-knight-pc-was-a-1714915219|website=[[Kotaku]]|publisher=[[Gawker Media]]|accessdate=July 1, 2015|date=July 1, 2015}}</ref> It would later be revealed that work on the PC port had been handed over to Polish developers QLOC. On August 28, 2015, Warner Bros. announced the cancellation of the PlayStation 3 and Xbox 360 ports (originally scheduled for release at a later unspecified date) of ''Mortal Kombat X'' due to the inability to get the version for the last gen consoles to reach the quality standards set by the current generation.<ref>{{cite web|title=Mortal Kombat X PlayStation 3, Xbox 360 Versions Cancelled|url=http://www.ign.com/articles/2015/08/28/mortal-kombat-x-playstation-3-xbox-360-versions-cancelled|work=[[IGN]]|first=Cassidee|last=Moser|accessdate=August 28, 2015}}</ref> NetherRealm Studios community specialist Tyler Lansdown initially stated that Kombat Pack 2, ''Mortal Kombat XL'', and the enhanced online netcode would not be available on the PC version.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Walker|first1=Ian|title=Mortal Kombat X on PC Won't Receive Kombat Pack 2 Content|url=http://shoryuken.com/2016/01/20/mortal-kombat-x-on-pc-wont-receive-kombat-pack-2-content/|website=shoryuken.com|publisher=Shoryuken|accessdate=January 20, 2016}}</ref> However, on August 25, 2016 an open beta test period of the online functionality of ''XL'' was announced for the PC,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.pcgamer.com/mortal-kombat-xl-coming-to-pc-free-open-beta-this-weekend/|title=Mortal Kombat XL coming to PC, free open beta this weekend|publisher=PCGamer.com|date=August 26, 2016}}</ref> and ultimately a release date was set for October 4, 2016.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://shoryuken.com/2016/09/28/new-mortal-kombat-x-balance-patch-coming-on-october-4th-to-coincide-with-pc-release-of-mortal-kombat-xl/|title=New Mortal Kombat X Balance Patch Coming on October 4th to Coincide with PC Release of Mortal Kombat XL|publisher=Shoryuken.com|date=September 28, 2016}}</ref>\n\n==Release==\n''Mortal Kombat X'' was released worldwide (except Germany) for PC, PlayStation 4, and Xbox One on April 14, 2015. For reasons relating to the initial refusal by the German [[USK]] to issue the game with an age rating, the official German release of ''Mortal Kombat X'' was delayed until September 1, 2015. The game's ''Kollector's Edition'' includes a figurine of Scorpion and the Gold Scorpion skin, as well as future access to Kombat Pack 1.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://nichegamer.net/2015/02/kollectors-edition-for-mortal-kombat-x-revealed-comes-with-scorpion-statue/ |title=Kollector's Edition for Mortal Kombat X Revealed, Comes with Scorpion Statue - Niche Gamer |work=nichegamer.net |accessdate=February 19, 2015}}</ref> Simultaneously with the release of Kombat Pack 2 and ''Mortal Kombat XL'', the game received a free major update that introduced balance changes, one new stage (\"The Pit\"), several stage brutalities, and rollback-based [[netcode]] similar to [[GGPO]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.polygon.com/2016/1/15/10776282/mortal-kombat-x-network-code-ggpo|title=Mortal Kombat X is getting a networking code overhaul|publisher=Polygon}}</ref>\n\n===Downloadable content===\nBefore the game's launch, Goro was offered as a pre-order bonus. Later on, upon the game's release, he was also made available for purchase.<ref name=\"goro\">{{cite web |url=http://www.gamespot.com/articles/mortal-kombat-x-launching-april-2015-goro-fighter-/1100-6422129/ |title=Mortal Kombat X launching April 2015, Goro fighter revealed!|publisher=Gamespot.com|accessdate=January 17, 2015}}</ref>\n\nThe game has also received numerous [[downloadable content]] (DLC) packages, containing skin packs and occasionally new characters, such as the Ultimate Horror Pack, which includes Jason and horror-themed skins for Ermac, Reptile and Mileena; or the Predator/Prey Pack, which includes Predator and Predator-themed skins for Johnny Cage, Scorpion and a skin for Jax with the likeness and voice of actor [[Carl Weathers]] from the first ''[[Predator (film)|Predator]]'' film.\n\nOn March 13, 2015, [[Jason Voorhees]] from the ''[[Friday the 13th (franchise)|Friday the 13th]]'' franchise was announced as the first downloadable bonus character in the downloadable Kombat Pack season-pass bundle.<ref name=\"Mortal Kombat Online\">{{cite web|url=http://www.mortalkombatonline.com/content/News/read.cds?article=2318|title=Jason Voorhees Revealed For Mortal Kombat X Kombat Pass|publisher=Mortal Kombat Online|date=March 13, 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last=Karmali |first=Luke |url=http://www.ign.com/articles/2015/03/13/jason-voorhees-confirmed-for-mortal-kombat-x |title=Jason Voorhees Confirmed For Mortal Kombat X |publisher=IGN.com |date=March 13, 2015 |accessdate=April 6, 2015}}</ref> One week later, [[Predator (fictional species)|Predator]], from [[Predator (franchise)|the eponymous franchise]], was revealed as the second DLC guest character after he was inadvertently leaked by the [[Xbox Games Store]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ign.com/articles/2015/03/20/predator-dlc-character-outed-for-mortal-kombat-x|title=Predator DLC Character Outed for Mortal Kombat X|author=Michael Martin|work=[[IGN]]|date=March 19, 2015|accessdate=March 20, 2015}}</ref> with Tremor from ''[[Mortal Kombat: Special Forces]]'' and Tanya from ''[[Mortal Kombat 4]]'' later rounding out the cast of the Kombat Pack.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Chavez |first1=Steven |title=Tremor, Tanya, Predator, and Jason Voorhees are Mortal Kombat X's Kombat Pack characters, Liu Kang also confirmed |url=http://www.eventhubs.com/news/2015/mar/20/tremor-tanya-predator-and-jason-voorhees-are-mortal-kombat-xs-kombat-pack-characters/|website=eventhubs.com|publisher=Eventhubs|accessdate=March 20, 2015}}</ref> Ultimately, the pack was revealed to include all of the content in the Samurai Pack, Ultimate Horror Pack, Klassic Pack #1, Predator/Prey Pack and Klassic Pack #2.<ref>{{cite web |author= |url=http://community.wbgames.com/t5/Official-Announcements/What-you-get-with-the-Kombat-Pack/m-p/433947 |title=What you get with the Kombat Pack! - WB Games |publisher=Community.wbgames.com |date=March 27, 2015 |accessdate=April 6, 2015 |archive-url=http://archive.wikiwix.com/cache/20150408005951/http://community.wbgames.com/t5/Official-Announcements/What-you-get-with-the-Kombat-Pack/m-p/433947 |archive-date=April 8, 2015 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\nOn September 2, 2015, [[Ed Boon]] teased a Kombat Pack 2 DLC, which would include four new characters.<ref>{{cite web | author= |url=http://www.ign.com/articles/2015/09/03/new-mortal-kombat-x-dlc-announced-for-2016 |title= New Mortal Kombat X DLC Announced for 2016 |publisher=IGN.com | date=September 3, 2015| accessdate= }}</ref> On December 3, 2015, the characters for Kombat Pack 2 were revealed to be Bo' Rai Cho from ''[[Mortal Kombat: Deadly Alliance]]'', a new character named [[Triborg]] (a cyborg character that features [[Cyrax]], [[Sektor]], [[Smoke (Mortal Kombat)|Smoke]] and [[Sub-Zero (Mortal Kombat)|Cyber Sub-Zero]] as its variations), [[Leatherface]] from ''[[The Texas Chainsaw Massacre (franchise)|The Texas Chainsaw Massacre]]'' franchise, and the [[Alien (creature in Alien franchise)|Alien]] from [[Alien (franchise)|the eponymous franchise]]. Kombat Pack 2 also makes Goro playable for those who didn't have him as a pre-order bonus, and includes Kold War Scorpion, Kold War Pack, Apocalypse Pack and Klassic Fatalities #1 and #2. Kombat Pack 2 was ultimately announced for release on March 1, 2016 only on PlayStation 4 and Xbox One, marking the beginning of a period where the [[Microsoft Windows]] port was left aside for any updates and new DLC releases. Eventually it was released on PC on October 4, 2016 along with the PC release of ''Mortal Kombat XL''.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.eurogamer.net/articles/2016-10-05-it-looks-like-warner-has-fixed-mortal-kombat-x-on-pc|title=It looks like Warner has fixed Mortal Kombat X on PC|publisher=EuroGamer.net}}</ref>\n\n===''Mortal Kombat XL''===\nOn January 20, 2016, coinciding with the official announcement of Kombat Pack 2, NetherRealm Studios announced a new release of the game, called ''Mortal Kombat XL'' to be released simultaneously with said Kombat Pack, which would include all previously released downloadable content up to Kombat Pack 2. ''Mortal Kombat XL'' was then released for Xbox One and PlayStation 4 on March 1, 2016 in North America, and March 4, 2016 in Europe.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Kato|first1=Matthew|title=Mortal Kombat XL Includes Every Fighter, Skin & Fatality|url=http://www.gameinformer.com/b/news/archive/2016/01/20/mortal-kombat-xl-includes-every-fighter-skin-and-fatality.aspx|publisher=[[Game Informer]]|accessdate=January 20, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last1=Osborn|first1=Alex|title=Mortal Kombat XL Announced|url=http://www.ign.com/articles/2016/01/20/mortal-kombat-xl-announced?|website=IGN|accessdate=January 20, 2016}}</ref>\n\nWith the PC having been left behind after Kombat Pack 1, in August 2016 Ed Boon ran a poll on Twitter, which resulted in 45% of 10,000 voters saying they wanted ''Mortal Kombat XL'' for PC. After it ended, he posted the results, suggesting they would be acted upon.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://twitter.com/noobde/status/759575661535191040|title=Ed Boon Twitter poll|publisher=Ed Boon@Twitter}}</ref> Shortly after, an online-only beta was officially released on August 25, 2016 as a free-to-play title on [[Steam (service)|Steam]] in order to test the enhanced netcode, which lasted through September 1, 2016.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.polygon.com/2016/8/25/12646130/mortal-kombat-xl-kombat-pack-2-pc-release-steam|title=Mortal Kombat XL and Kombat Pack 2 now available on PC|first=Michael|last=McWhertor|work=[[Polygon (website)|Polygon]]|date=August 25, 2016|accessdate=August 26, 2016}}</ref> As soon as the beta ended, it was announced that ''Mortal Kombat XL'' (both as a full game for purchase, and as an update for ''Mortal Kombat X'' owners) would become available alongside the Kombat Pack 2 DLC on October 4, 2016, along with the updates that would bring the PC port back to parity with its console counterparts.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://testyourmight.com/threads/mkxl-enhanced-online-beta-feedback-kp2-coming-october-4th.61403/|title=MKXL ENHANCED ONLINE BETA FEEDBACK; KP2 COMING OCTOBER 4TH|publisher=TestYourMight| date=September 1, 2016| access-date=September 1, 2016}}</ref> As revealed by the game's updated intro credits, the porting of ''XL'' to the PC was handled by QLOC, in opposition to the previous problematic releases, by High Voltage Software. Coinciding with the release of XL for PC, an XL Pack was announced for existing owners of the game, which provides all of the previously existing DLC in a single package. Also coinciding with the release of the PC port of ''Mortal Kombat XL'' was a balance patch affecting most of the 33 characters in the roster in all three of the game's platforms.<ref>{{cite web|title=Patch Notes 10-4-16|url=http://community.wbgames.com/t5/Latest-Updates/Patch-Notes-10-4-16/ba-p/1297392|website=WB GAMES COMMUNITY|accessdate=October 4, 2016}}</ref>\n\n==Related media==\n\n===Mobile game===\nOn March 2, 2015, NetherRealm Studios announced that their mobile division would release an [[iOS]]/[[Android (operating system)|Android]] version of ''Mortal Kombat X'' in April 2015. The mobile game is described as a \"free-to-play fighting/card-battler hybrid\" and players would be able to unlock content in the console version of the game by playing the mobile version (and vice versa).<ref>{{cite web|title=A mobile version of Mortal Kombat X is also in development|url=http://www.warpzoned.com/2015/03/a-mobile-version-of-mortal-kombat-x-is-also-in-development/|website=Warp Zoned|date=March 2, 2015}}</ref> The iOS version was released worldwide on April 7, 2015, while the Android version was [[soft launch]]ed on April 21, 2015 in select Asian countries<ref name=\"androidasia\">{{cite web|url=http://news.softpedia.com/news/Mortal-Kombat-X-for-Android-Released-in-Google-Play-Store-But-It-s-Not-Available-to-All-479121.shtml|title=Mortal Kombat X Mobile released in select countries}}</ref> and was officially launched worldwide on May 4, 2015.<ref name=\"mkxandroid\"/>\n\nWith the 1.11 update version of the mobile game released on December 6, 2016, Freddy Krueger who appeared as a DLC character in ''[[Mortal Kombat (2011 video game)|MK9]]'' was added as a mobile-exclusive character using his signature moves and X-Ray attack from MK9.<ref name=\"mkxfreddy\">{{cite web|url=https://twitter.com/NetherRealm/status/806994436399960068|title=Freddy Krueger makes a splash on MKX Mobile}}</ref> On the update 1.13, Jade and Baraka were also added in the game as mobile exclusives, using their X-Rays from MK9. The latest version as of September 2017 (version 1.14) includes the popularly demanded Takeda, as well as the most recent addition to the ninja cast, Tremor.{{citation needed|date=September 2017}} By October 4, another update was released, featuring Goro (Klassic and Tigrar Fury) and Shao Kahn. A February 2018 update introduced Bo' Rai Cho and Kintaro. An October 2018 update introduced console DLC character [[Leatherface]]. In February 2019, the game was renamed ''Mortal Kombat Mobile'' with its 2.0 update with a vast overhaul of new features for ''[[Mortal Kombat 11]]''. Furthermore, the 2.0 update upgraded its graphics engine from [[Unreal Engine 3]] to [[Unreal Engine 4]].\n\nThe app has 50 million downloads on Android.<ref>https://play.google.com/store/apps/details?id=com.wb.goog.mkx</ref>\n\n===Promotions===\nPrior to the game's release, [[DC Comics]] published a comic book series based on the game, with the first issue released on January 6, 2015.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.comixology.com/Mortal-Kombat-X-2015-1/digital-comic/176368?ref=Y29taWMvdmlldy9kZXNrdG9wL3NsaWRlckxpc3Qvc2VyaWVz |title=Mortal Kombat X (2015-) #1 - Comics by comiXology |work=comixology.com |accessdate=February 19, 2015}}</ref> The debut trailer and opening cinematic features an original track by [[Wiz Khalifa]] titled \"Can't Be Stopped\".<ref>Jang, Esther. (June 3, 2014). [http://www.latinpost.com/articles/14123/20140603/wiz-khalifa-hot-new-song-2014-rapper-premieres-cant-be-stopped-in-mortal-kombat-x-trailer-watch.htm \"Wiz Khalifa Hot New Song 2014: Rapper Premieres 'Can't Be Stopped' in 'Mortal Kombat X' Trailer &#91;Watch&#93;\"] ''Latin Post''</ref> The official television commercial and launch trailer for the game were directed by [[System of a Down]] member [[Shavo Odadjian]] and featured the band's 2001 track \"[[Chop Suey!]]\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.gamespot.com/articles/mortal-kombat-x-uses-system-of-a-down-track-for-ne/1100-6426209/|title=Mortal Kombat X Uses System of a Down Track for New Live-Action Trailer|first=Eddie|last=Makuch|publisher=GameSpot.com|date=March 27, 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite av media|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=4faAvsMMpFg|title=Mortal Kombat X - Official Launch Trailer - PS4, PS3|date=April 6, 2015|work=YouTube}}</ref> The ''Mortal Kombat X'' logo was featured on [[NASCAR]] driver [[Erik Jones]]' #20 [[Xfinity Series]] car (sponsored by [[GameStop]]) that won the [[O'Reilly Auto Parts 300]] on April 10, 2015.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.sbnation.com/nascar/2015/4/11/8386683/nascar-texas-motor-speedway-2015-o-reilly-auto-parts-300-winner-erik-jones|title=18-year-old Erik Jones wins Xfinity Series race over Brad Keselowski, Dale Earnhardt Jr.| first=Jordan| last=Bianchi|publisher=SBNation.com|date=April 10, 2015|accessdate=April 12, 2015}}</ref> ''Mortal Kombat X'' has been used in [[eSports]] competitions, with international tournaments in Europe, Asia, and North America with $1,000 weekly tournament prizes starting on April 19, 2015 with a season final on July 11, 2015 worth at least $100,000.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://en.pro.eslgaming.com/mkx/proleague/|title=ESL MKX ProLeague - the first international tournament for Mortal Kombat X|accessdate=May 14, 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150402080900/http://en.pro.eslgaming.com/mkx/proleague/|archive-date=April 2, 2015|url-status=dead}}</ref> The ESL Pro League Season 1 Finals were won by Critical Reaction's Dominique \"Sonic Fox\" McLean using Kitana with Erron Black as a secondary. McLean earned a grand total of $60,000 from the Season 1 Finals.<ref>{{cite web|title=ESL MKX Pro League Season One Finals Overview|url=http://en.pro.eslgaming.com/mkx/proleague/news/esl-mkx-pro-league-season-one-finals-overview/|website=eslgaming.com|publisher=ESL Pro League Gaming|accessdate=July 27, 2015}}</ref> Season Two of the ESL Pro League for ''Mortal Kombat X'' began on October 18, 2015 and concluded in early 2016.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Tim Static|title=DETAILS ON THE ESL MORTAL KOMBAT X PRO LEAGUE SEASON 2; PRESEASON STARTS OCTOBER 18TH|url=http://testyourmight.com/threads/details-on-the-esl-mortal-kombat-x-pro-league-season-2-preseason-starts-october-18th.56563/|website=testyourmight.com|publisher=Test Your Might|accessdate=October 13, 2015}}</ref>\n\n==Reception==\n{{Video game reviews\n| MC = iOS: 66/100<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.metacritic.com/game/ios/mortal-kombat-x |title=Mortal Kombat X for iPhone/iPad Reviews |website=[[Metacritic]] |publisher=[[CBS Interactive]] |accessdate=July 11, 2018}}</ref><br />XONE: 86/100<ref name=\"MCXONE\">{{cite web |url=http://www.metacritic.com/game/xbox-one/mortal-kombat-x |title=Mortal Kombat X for Xbox One Reviews |website=[[Metacritic]] |publisher=[[CBS Interactive]] |accessdate=April 30, 2015}}</ref><br />PS4: 83/100<ref name=\"MCPS4\">{{cite web |url=http://www.metacritic.com/game/playstation-4/mortal-kombat-x |title=Mortal Kombat X for PlayStation 4 Reviews |website=[[Metacritic]] |publisher=[[CBS Interactive]] |accessdate=July 11, 2018}}</ref><br />PC: 76/100<ref name=\"MCPC\">{{cite web |url=http://www.metacritic.com/game/pc/mortal-kombat-x |title=Mortal Kombat X for PC Reviews |website=[[Metacritic]] |publisher=[[CBS Interactive]] |accessdate=April 30, 2015}}</ref><br />(''XL'') PS4: 85/100<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.metacritic.com/game/playstation-4/mortal-kombat-xl |title=Mortal Kombat XL for PlayStation 4 Reviews |website=[[Metacritic]] |publisher=[[CBS Interactive]] |accessdate=July 11, 2018}}</ref><br />(''XL'') PC: 84/100<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.metacritic.com/game/pc/mortal-kombat-xl |title=Mortal Kombat XL for PC Reviews |website=[[Metacritic]] |publisher=[[CBS Interactive]] |accessdate=July 11, 2018}}</ref>\n| Destruct = 8/10<ref name=\"Destructoid review\">{{cite web |last=Carter |first=Chris |date=April 14, 2015 |url=http://www.destructoid.com/review-mortal-kombat-x-290360.phtml |title=Review: Mortal Kombat X |publisher=[[Destructoid]] |accessdate=April 14, 2015}}</ref>\n| EGM = 7.5/10<ref>{{cite web |last=Carsillo |first=Ray |date=April 13, 2015 |url=http://www.egmnow.com/articles/reviews/mortal-kombat-x-review/ |title=Mortal Kombat X review |publisher=[[Electronic Gaming Monthly]] |accessdate=April 13, 2015 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150415233431/http://www.egmnow.com/articles/reviews/mortal-kombat-x-review/ |archive-date=April 15, 2015 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n| GI = 9.25/10<ref name=\"GI\">{{cite web |last=Shea |first=Brian |date=April 13, 2015 |url=http://www.gameinformer.com/games/mortal_kombat_x/b/playstation4/archive/2015/04/13/mortal-kombat-x-review-game-informer.aspx |title=A Deadly Alliance Of Old And New - Mortal Kombat X - PlayStation 4 |publisher=[[Game Informer]] |accessdate=April 13, 2015}}</ref>\n| GameRev = {{Rating|4|5}}<ref name=\"Game Revolution review\">{{cite web |last=Tan |first=Nick |date=April 13, 2015 |url=http://www.gamerevolution.com/review/mortal-kombat-x |title=Mortal Kombat X Review |publisher=[[Game Revolution]] |accessdate=April 13, 2015}}</ref>\n| GSpot = 8/10<ref name=\"GSpot\">{{cite web|last=Brown |first=Peter |date=April 17, 2015 |url=http://www.gamespot.com/reviews/mortal-kombat-x-review/1900-6416101/ |title=Mortal Kombat X Review |publisher=[[GameSpot]] |accessdate=April 17, 2015}}</ref>\n| GRadar = {{Rating|3.5|5}}<ref name=\"GRadar\">{{cite web |last=Sullivan |first=Lucas |date=April 13, 2015 |url=http://www.gamesradar.com/mortal-kombat-x-review/ |title=Mortal Kombat X review |publisher=[[GamesRadar]] |accessdate=April 13, 2015}}</ref>\n| GT = 8.4/10<ref name=\"GT\">{{cite web |last=Huber |first=Michael |date=April 15, 2015 |url=http://www.gametrailers.com/reviews/r5e3hy/mortal-kombat-x-review |title=Mortal Kombat X Review |publisher=[[GameTrailers]] |accessdate=April 15, 2015}}</ref>\n| GB = {{Rating|4|5}}<ref>{{cite web |last=Gerstmann |first=Jeff |date=April 13, 2015 |url=http://www.giantbomb.com/reviews/mortal-kombat-x-review/1900-703/ |title=Mortal Kombat X Review |publisher=[[Giant Bomb]] |accessdate=April 13, 2015}}</ref>\n| IGN = 8.4/10<ref name=\"IGN\">{{cite web |last=Ingenito |first=Vince |date=April 13, 2015 |url=http://www.ign.com/articles/2015/04/13/mortal-kombat-x-review |title=Mortal Kombat X Review |publisher=[[IGN]] |accessdate=April 13, 2015}}</ref>\n| PCGUS = 69/100<ref name=\"PCGUS\">{{cite web |last=Elliot |first=Matt |date=April 21, 2015 |url=http://www.pcgamer.com/mortal-kombat-x-review/ |title=Mortal Kombat X review |publisher=[[PC Gamer]] |accessdate=April 21, 2015}}</ref>\n| Poly = 8.5/10<ref name=\"Poly\">{{cite web |last=McWhertor |first=Michael |date=April 13, 2015 |url=http://www.polygon.com/2015/4/13/8364929/mortal-kombat-x-review-PS4-Xbox-One |title=Mortal Kombat X review: new blood |publisher=[[Polygon (website)|Polygon]] |accessdate=May 2, 2015}}</ref>\n| VG = 8/10<ref name=\"VideoGamer.com review\">{{cite web |last=Phipps |first=Brett |date=April 13, 2015 |url=http://www.videogamer.com/reviews/mortla_kombat_x_review.html |title=Mortal Kombat X Review |work=VideoGamer.com |accessdate=April 13, 2015}}</ref>\n| rev1 = ''[[VentureBeat]]''\n| rev1Score = 65/100<ref name=\"VentureBeat\">{{cite web|url=https://venturebeat.com/2015/04/16/mortal-kombat-x-i-love-you-but-i-hate-you-look-its-komplicated/|title=Mortal Kombat X, I love you...but I hate you. Look, it's komplicated|first=Stephen|last=Kleckner |publisher=VentureBeat|date=April 16, 2015|accessdate=April 16, 2015}}</ref>\n| rev2 = ''[[TouchArcade]]''\n| rev2Score = iOS: {{rating|4|5}}<ref>{{cite web |url=https://toucharcade.com/2015/04/08/mortal-kombat-x-review/ |title='Mortal Kombat X' Review \u2013 Vengeance Feels A Lot Like Justice |last=Musgrave |first=Shaun |date=April 8, 2015 |website=[[TouchArcade]] |accessdate=July 11, 2018}}</ref>\n| award1Pub = [[The Game Awards 2015]]\n| award1 = Best Fighting Game\n| award2Pub = [[Game Informer]]\n| award2 = Best Fighting Game<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.gameinformer.com/b/features/archive/2016/01/06/game-informer-best-of-2015-awards.aspx?PageIndex=4&PostPageIndex=2|title=Game Informer Best Of 2015 Awards|publisher=[[Game Informer]]}}</ref>\n| award3Pub = [[IGN]]\n| award3 = Best Fighting Game<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ign.com/wikis/best-of-2015/Best_Fighting_Game|title=IGN Best of 2015|publisher=IGN}}</ref>\n| award4Pub = [[Academy of Interactive Arts & Sciences]]\n| award4 = Fighting Game of the Year\n}}\n\n''Mortal Kombat X'' received mostly positive reviews. Aggregating review website [[Metacritic]] gave the Xbox One version 86/100 based on 21 reviews,<ref name=\"MCXONE\" /> the PlayStation 4 version 83/100 based on 81 reviews,<ref name=\"MCPS4\" /> and the Microsoft Windows version 76/100 based on 10 reviews.<ref name=\"MCPC\" /> It became the fastest selling game in the history of the ''Mortal Kombat'' series and topped the US<ref>{{cite web|url=http://gamerant.com/mortal-kombat-x-sales-ps4/|title='Mortal Kombat X' Tops PS4 Sales Charts|date=May 13, 2015|work=Game Rant|accessdate=October 7, 2015}}</ref> and UK<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.chart-track.co.uk/index.jsp?c=p%2Fsoftware%2Fuk%2Farchive%2Findex_test.jsp&ct=110032&arch=t&lyr=2015&year=2015&week=17|title=UK ARCHIVE SOFTWARE CHARTS|publisher=chart-track.co.uk}}</ref> PlayStation 4 sales charts in the month of release.\n\nBrian Shea of ''[[Game Informer]]'' called ''Mortal Kombat X'' \"more than the continuation of NetherRealm's successful vision for the franchise; it's one of the best fighting games in years\", adding that the core gameplay was complex and varied while he enjoyed the multiplayer options.<ref name=\"GI\" /> [[GameSpot]]'s Peter Brown enjoyed the overall gameplay, saying it had \"the best fighting mechanics of any game in the series\" but was critical of the downloadable content as \"there's so much to love about the new ''Mortal Kombat'' that it's a shame to see such blatant [[monetization]] practices overlap with your experience\".<ref name=\"GSpot\" /> Lucas Sullivan of [[GamesRadar]] described the story mode as \"ceaselessly entertaining\", having \"great voice-acting and a surprisingly enjoyable script\", and \"a pretty tough act to follow\", criticizing the other single-player modes outside of the main story, and \"sparse\" tutorial options.<ref name=\"GRadar\" />\n\n[[Destructoid]]'s Chris Carter scored the game an 8 out of 10 and called it \"one of the biggest fighting games of 2015\". Carter felt that as more characters are added via DLC, the game will get better over time.<ref name=\"Destructoid review\"/> ''VideoGamer.com''{{'s}} Brett Phipps gave the game an 8/10 and called it \"absurd, gruesome ridiculous fun\". Phipps mostly praised the story, character gameplay variety, and gore, but was annoyed by online \"hiccups\".<ref name=\"VideoGamer.com review\"/> Nick Tan from [[Game Revolution]] commended the gameplay, particularly complimenting the character variations, environmental attacks, Brutalities, the Krypt, and the Tower system. Tan also liked the overall presentation and the story's concept, but missed Stage Fatalities and tag-team matches, disliked the story's ending, and felt that the game was purposefully \"truncated\".<ref name=\"Game Revolution review\"/>\n\nMichael Huber of [[GameTrailers]] called it a \"superb entry in the franchise\", noting the gameplay, story mode and new online components.<ref name=\"GT\" /> Vince Ingenito of [[IGN]] gave it a score of 8.4. He claimed that ''Mortal Kombat X'' was the best ''Mortal Kombat'' game in the franchise's history, lauding it as deeper, mechanically richer and more fully featured than the previous ''Mortal Kombat'' games. He also praised the presence of the new characters as the major roster shakeup made the game feel new and exciting to longtime series fans and casual fans.<ref name=\"IGN\" /> Michael McWhertor of [[Polygon (website)|Polygon]] called the game \"one of the best fighting games in the series\", praising the gameplay in addition to the newer systems in place and overall presentation.<ref name=\"Poly\" /> Stephen Kleckner of [[VentureBeat]] was more critical of the game, citing in his opinion confusing move animations, a system favoring close range mid-to-high combos, having to use the block button to execute a run, poor online play, and easy Fatality DLC. He also mentioned an issue where save data would be erased due to a bug in the PC version.<ref name=\"VentureBeat\" /> Matt Elliott of [[PC Gamer]] had mixed feelings about the online gameplay and said that \"''Mortal Kombat'' online simply isn't sturdy enough to remain competitive\".<ref name=\"PCGUS\"/>\n\nIn October 2015, Warner Bros. confirmed that ''Mortal Kombat X'' had sold more than 5 million copies worldwide by then.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Hussain|first1=Tamoor|title=Batman: Arkham Knight, Mortal Kombat X Sell 5 Million Each Worldwide, Report Says|url=http://www.gamespot.com/articles/batman-arkham-knight-mortal-kombat-x-sell-5-millio/1100-6431342/|website=gamespot.com|publisher=GameSpot|accessdate=October 13, 2015}}</ref> It was the fastest-selling game in the franchise and was the ninth-best-selling retail game of 2015 in the United States.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.gamespot.com/articles/mortal-kombat-x-enjoys-biggest-launch-in-franchise/1100-6426680/|title=Mortal Kombat X Enjoys \"Biggest Launch\" in Franchise History|first=Eddie|last=Makuch|work=[[GameSpot]]|date=April 16, 2015|accessdate=March 14, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://venturebeat.com/2016/01/14/2015-npd-the-10-best-selling-games-of-the-year/|title=2015 NPD: The 10 best-selling games of the year|first=Jeff|last=Grubb|work=[[VentureBeat]]|date=January 14, 2016|accessdate=January 14, 2016}}</ref> The first-month sales of the game is higher than the first-month sales of every game released in April 2016.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.gameinformer.com/b/news/archive/2016/05/12/dark-souls-iii-leads-the-pack-during-a-slow-month-in-april-npd-report.aspx|title=Dark Souls III Leads The Pack During A Slow Month In April NPD Report|first=Ben|last=Reeves|publisher=[[Game Informer]]|date=May 12, 2016|accessdate=May 14, 2016}}</ref>\n\n===Awards===\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! colspan=\"4\" style=\"background:#B0C4DE;\" | List of awards and nominations\n|-\n! style=\"background:#ccc;\" | Award\n! style=\"background:#ccc;\" | Category\n! style=\"background:#ccc;\" | Result\n|-\n| [[The Game Awards 2015]]\n| Best Fighting Game\n| {{won}}<ref name=\"TGA: Nominees\">{{cite web | url = http://thegameawards.com/nominees/ | title = Nominees {{!}} The Game Awards 2015 | date = November 12, 2015 | website = [[The Game Awards]] | publisher = [[Ola Balola]] | accessdate = November 13, 2015 | url-status = dead | archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20151114024126/http://thegameawards.com/nominees/ | archivedate = November 14, 2015 | df = mdy-all }}</ref>\n|-\n| rowspan=2| 2015 [[National Academy of Video Game Trade Reviewers|NAVGTR Awards]]\n| Game, Franchise Fighting\n| {{won}}<ref name=\"navgtr\">{{cite web|title=NAVGTR Awards (2015)|url=http://navgtr.org/winners/2015-winners|website=National Academy of Video Game Trade Reviewers}}</ref>\n|-\n| Camera Direction in a Game Engine\n| {{nom}}<ref name=\"navgtr\" />\n|}\n\n==Sequel==\n{{main|Mortal Kombat 11}}\n\nA direct sequel to ''Mortal Kombat X'', ''[[Mortal Kombat 11]]'' was announced at [[The Game Awards 2018]]. It was once again developed by NetherRealm Studios and released worldwide on April 23, 2019 for [[Microsoft Windows]], [[Nintendo Switch]], [[PlayStation 4]], and [[Xbox One]].\n\n==Notes==\n{{notelist}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{Official website|https://www.mortalkombat.com/}}\n\n{{Wikiquote}}\n{{Mortal Kombat}}\n